 Operations Command]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.knox.edu/fridovich-david-74|title= David Fridovich '74|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Hobart R. Gay]] 1917 \u2014 [[U.S. Army]] general, served under General [[George S. Patton]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://library.knox.edu/archives/manuscripts/hobart_gay.htm|title= Hobart R. Gay Manuscript Collection|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Robert Hanssen]] 1966 \u2014 [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] agent convicted of spying for [[Soviet Union]] and [[Russia]] in 2001, subject of film ''[[Breach (film)|Breach]]'' (2007)<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url= http://www.britannica.com/biography/Robert-Hanssen|title= Robert Hanssen: American law enforcement agent and spy|encyclopedia= Encyclopaedia Britannica|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Otto Harbach]] 1895 \u2014 songwriter for whom Knox's Harbach Theater is named<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/exhibits/bio/C105|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090109134637/http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/exhibits/bio/C105|url-status= dead|archive-date= January 9, 2009|title= Otto Harbach Biography|publisher= Songwriters Hall of Fame|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Don Harmon]] 1988 \u2014 Illinois State Senator (Democrat) and Senate President Pro Tempore\n*[[Loyal M. Haynes]] 1918 \u2014 [[Brigadier General]] in [[United States Army|U.S. Army]], commanding general of 2nd Division Artillery Unit in Korean War and survivor of the [[1946 C-53 Skytrooper crash on the Gauli Glacier]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k8d2YX43hMoC&pg=PA236|title= Disaster in Korea: The Chinese Confront MacArthur|publisher= Roy E. Appleman|accessdate= June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=YipJAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA111|title= Knox College Catalog|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thehistoryblog.com/archives/18829|title= Teens find famed 1946 plane wreck in Swiss glacier|publisher= The History Blog|accessdate= August 20, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171103004657/http://www.thehistoryblog.com/archives/18829|archive-date= 2017-11-03|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n* [[B. J. Hollars]] 2007 \u2014 author\n* [[Bob Jamieson]]  \u2014 [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] news correspondent<ref>{{cite web|url= http://departments.knox.edu/newsarchive/news_events/2003/x3517.html|title= Bob Jamieson at Knox Talks, Feb. 11|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Frank J. Jirka, Jr.]] 1944 \u2014 former president of [[American Medical Association]]<ref>{{cite news|url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-10-04/news/0010040176_1_ama-trustee-illinois-state-medical-society-macneal-hospital|title= Dr. Frank J. Jirka Jr., Ex-ama President|newspaper= Chicago Tribune|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Whitcomb Judson]]  \u2014 inventor of the [[zipper]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://historyofscience2009.blogspot.com/2009/03/whitcomb-l-judson-zipper.html|title= Whitcomb L. Judson- Zipper|publisher= historyofscience2009.blogspot.com|accessdate= January 7, 2016|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151218150531/http://historyofscience2009.blogspot.com/2009/03/whitcomb-l-judson-zipper.html|archive-date= 2015-12-18|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n* [[James M. Kilts]] 1970 \u2014 former [[CEO]] of [[Gillette (brand)|Gillette]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=683964&privcapId=46401796|title= Executive Profile James M. Kilts|publisher= Bloomberg Business|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Ismat Kittani]] 1951 \u2014 former Iraqi Ambassador to the [[United Nations]] and [[President of the United Nations General Assembly]]; helped start Knox's Honor System<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.un.org/en/ga/president/bios/bio36.shtml|title= Ismat T. Kittani (Iraq)|publisher= General Assembly of the United Nations|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Alex Kuo]] 1961 \u2014 Distinguished Affiliated Scholar at Knox, author, winner of 2002 [[American Book Award]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.knox.edu/academics/majors-and-minors/english-literature/faculty/kuo-alex|title= Alex Kuo: Distinguished Affiliated Scholar|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Thomas Eugene Kurtz]] 1950 \u2014 co-inventor of [[BASIC]] computer language<ref>{{cite web|url= http://history.computer.org/pioneers/kurtz.html|title= Thomas E. Kurtz|publisher= Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Charles Wesley Leffingwell]] 1862 \u2014 editor of ''[[The Living Church]]'' magazine<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.illinoisancestors.org/knox/Biographies/leffingell_charles.html|title= The History of Knox County|publisher= illinoisancestors.org|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Lorenzo D. Lewelling]] \u2014 [[List of Governors of Kansas|12th]] [[Governor of Kansas]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_kansas/col2-content/main-content-list/title_lewelling_lorenzo.html|title= Kansas Governor Lorenzo Dow Lewelling|publisher= National Governors Association |accessdate= September 29, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Don Marquis]] \u2014 author and journalist<ref>{{cite web|url= http://donmarquis.org/knoxalumni.htm|title= Don Marquis Letter to Knox College Alumni|publisher= Don Marquis|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Edgar Lee Masters]] \u2014 poet and novelist, best known as author of ''[[Spoon River Anthology]]'' (1915)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.knox.edu/library/special-collections-and-archives/rare-books/edgar-lee-masters-collection|title= The Edgar Lee Masters Collection|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[S. S. McClure]] 1882 \u2014 [[muckraking]] journalism pioneer, founder of ''[[McClure's Magazine]]''<ref>{{cite web|url= http://indianajournalismhof.org/2005/01/samuel-s-mcclure/|title= SAMUEL S. MCCLURE \u00b7 2005|publisher= Indiana Journalism Hall of Fame|accessdate= January 8, 2016|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160118171354/http://indianajournalismhof.org/2005/01/samuel-s-mcclure/|archive-date= 2016-01-18|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n* [[Todd Monken (American football coach)|Todd Monken]] 1989 \u2014 former football head coach at Southern Mississippi University; currently offensive coordinator for NFL's [[Cleveland Browns]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.southernmiss.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/todd_monken_832058.html|title= Todd monken|publisher= Southern Mississippi University|accessdate= January 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Ander Monson]] 1997 \u2014 novelist and poet, author of ''Other Electricities'', and ''Vacationland'', a collection of poems<ref>{{cite web|url= http://departments.knox.edu/newsarchive/news_events/2005/x9693.html|title= Author Ander Monson|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[John Podesta]] 1971 \u2014 [[White House Chief of Staff|Chief of Staff]] for President [[Bill Clinton]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.law.georgetown.edu/faculty/podesta-john.cfm#|title= John Podesta, Distinguished Visitor from Practice|publisher= Georgetown University|accessdate= January 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Rose Polenzani]] \u2014 independent [[folk music|folk]] musician\n* [[Gene Rayburn]] \u2014 announcer for ''[[The Tonight Show]]''; host of ''[[The Match Game]]'' and other [[game show]]s\n* [[Hiram Rhodes Revels]] \u2014 AME and Methodist Episcopal minister, and first black [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] (1870\u20131871)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.knox.edu/library/special-collections-and-archives/college-archives/knox-college-history/hiram-rhodes-revels|title= Hiram Rhodes Revels|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Barnabas Root]] 1870 \u2014 one of the first black men to receive a college degree in [[Illinois]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.knox.edu/library/special-collections-and-archives/college-archives/knox-college-history/barnabas-root|title= Barnabas Root|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 8, 2016|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160125115419/http://www.knox.edu/library/special-collections-and-archives/college-archives/knox-college-history/barnabas-root|archive-date= 2016-01-25|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n* [[Ezekiel S. Sampson]] \u2014 [[U.S. Representative]] and lawyer from [[Iowa]]<ref>{{cite dictionary|url= http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=S000025|title=SAMPSON, Ezekiel Silas (1831 - 1892)|dictionary= Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|accessdate= September 25, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Don Samuelson]] \u2014 [[List of Governors of Idaho|25th Governor]] of [[Idaho]] (1967\u20131971)<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_idaho/col2-content/main-content-list/title_samuelson_don.html|title= Idaho Governor Don William Samuelson|publisher= National Governors Association |accessdate= September 25, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Ellen Browning Scripps]] 1859 \u2014 newspaper magnate, philanthropist; helped found [[Scripps College]] and [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.scrippscollege.edu/about/ellen-browning-scripps|title= Ellen Browning Scripps|publisher= Scripps College|accessdate= January 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Robert Seibert]] 1963 \u2014 Professor Emeritus at Knox College and author of ''Politics and Change in the Middle East''<ref>{{cite web|url= http://departments.knox.edu/newsarchive/news_events/2004/rseibert.html|title= Robert Seibert|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Joseph J. Sisco]] 1941 \u2014 diplomat under [[Henry Kissinger]]; president of [[American University]] (1976\u20131980)<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A8945-2004Nov23.html|title= Diplomat Joseph J. Sisco Dies at 85; Served as AU President in 1970s|newspaper= Washington Post|accessdate= January 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Zack Stephenson]] 2006 \u2014 Minnesota State Representative (2019\u2013present)\n* [[Dorothea Tanning]] 1932 \u2014 surrealist painter; wife of surrealist painter [[Max Ernst]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.dorotheatanning.org/dorothea-tanning.php|title= Dorothea Tanning: In Her Own Words|publisher= DorotheaTanning.org|accessdate= January 8, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Kathryn Tanquary]] 2010 \u2014 author of juvenile fiction novel ''[[The Night Parade]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.knox.edu/Documents/PDFs/Donors%202010/HRC10%20Class%202010.pdf|title=HRC10 Class of 2010|date=2010|website=knox.edu|publisher=Knox College|access-date=2016-12-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220100121/https://www.knox.edu/Documents/PDFs/Donors%202010/HRC10%20Class%202010.pdf|archive-date=2016-12-20|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sourcebooks.com/index.php?option=com_egdauthors&view=author&aid=A3108|title=Kathryn  Tanquary {{!}} Sourcebooks.com {{!}} Sourcebooks.com|website=www.sourcebooks.com|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref>\n* [[Mary Allen West]] 1855 \u2014 journalist and temperance worker\n* [[Allan Arthur Willman]] 1928 \u2014 classical pianist, 20th-century composer, chair of [[University of Wyoming]] music department<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.allan_arthur_willman.readwithhelp.com/|title= Allan Arthur Willman|publisher= readwithhelp.com|accessdate= January 8, 2016|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170810014028/http://www.allan_arthur_willman.readwithhelp.com/|archive-date= 2017-08-10|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n* [[Adam Pettinger]] 2001 - Statistical Programmer Analyst at the [[Mayo Clinic]] in Rochester, MN.  Executive treasurer of the board of elders for the Mayo Clinic Distinguished Gentlemen of [[Mayo Clinic]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Knox College (Illinois)}}\n* [http://www.knox.edu Official website]\n* [http://prairiefire.knox.edu Official athletics website]\n\n{{Midwest Conference navbox}}\n{{Annapolis Group}}\n{{Oberlin Group}}\n{{Associated Colleges of the Midwest}}\n\n{{Coord|40.942953|N|90.370982|W|source:dewiki_region:US-IL_type:edu|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Knox College (Illinois)| ]]\n[[Category:1837 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Education in Knox County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1837]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Members of the Annapolis Group]]\n[[Category:Members of the Oberlin Group]]\n[[Category:American manual labor schools]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Knox College (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Knox College\n| image_name = Knox College logo.png\n| motto = {{lang-la|Veritas}}\n| mottoeng = Truth\n| established = February 15, 1837\n| type = [[Private school|Private]]\n| endowment = [[US$]] 140 million (20 July 2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.knox.edu/news/knox-college-raises-close-to-15-million |title=Knox College Raises Close to $15 Million from Alumni, Friends - Knox College |website=Knox.edu |date= |accessdate=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n| president = [[Teresa Amott]]\n| city = [[Galesburg, Illinois|Galesburg]]\n| state = Illinois\n| country = United States\n| enrollment = 1,420\n| faculty = 120\n| campus = Small city\n| athletics = 21 varsity teams<br/>[[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]]<br/>[[Midwest Conference]]\n| mascot = Prairie Fire (nickname), Blaze (mascot)\n| colors = Purple and gold<br/> {{color box|#6C2DC7}}{{color box|#FDD017}}\n| website = [http://www.knox.edu/ www.knox.edu]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Knox College''' is a private [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]] in [[Galesburg, Illinois]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:George Washington Gale.jpg|thumb|George Washington Gale (1789\u20131861), founding father of Knox College]]\n[[File:Old Main Knox College.jpg|thumb|Old Main, the oldest building on the campus of Knox College]]\nKnox College was founded as '''Knox Manual Labor College''' in 1837 by a group of Presbyterians and Congregationalists organized by [[George Washington Gale]]. Gale was Galesburg and Knox's \"founding father\".<ref>{]cite web\n|title=The Origins of Knox College\n|first=Grant\n|last=Forssberg\n|accessdate=October 15, 2019\n|publisher=Knox College\n|url=https://www.knox.edu/about-knox/our-history/perspectives-on-knox-history/origins-of-knox-college}}</ref> He believed in the [[manual labor system]] of education, and had previously implemented it at America's first such college, the abolitionist but short-lived [[Oneida Institute]], near [[Utica, New York]].\n\nMany of the founders, including the Rev. [[Samuel Wright (minister)|Samuel Wright]], actively supported the [[Underground Railroad]].\n\nKnox has been known by its present name since 1857.{{citation needed|date=March 2011}} The name came about through a compromise among its founders. Though founded by a colony of [[Presbyterian Church in the United States of America|Presbyterians]] and [[Congregationalism in the United States|Congregationalists]], the county in which the college is located was already named [[Knox County, Illinois|Knox County]], after [[Henry Knox]], the first [[United States Secretary of War]]. Arguments have been made that the college was named for [[Calvinist]] leader [[John Knox]], but it is not certain for which Knox it was named (if not both). George Candee Gale, a great-great-grandson of two of the founders, explains that\n\n<blockquote>contrary to general belief, Knox was not named for either General Knox or the Scottish Presbyterian Knox, according to my father ...Some wanted the college named for one Knox, some for the other; so they compromised on KNOX. Certainly most of them were pious enough to want the churchman and fighters enough to want the soldier as well.\"<ref>Calkins, Earnest Elmo. (1937) ''They Broke the Prairie'', University of Illinois Press. {{ISBN|0-252-06094-6}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe presidency of [[Jonathan Blanchard (abolitionist)|Jonathan Blanchard]] led the school out of debt, but ignited a controversy about whether the school was loyal to the Congregational church or the Presbyterians. Both Gale and Blanchard were forced out of the school as a result.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fifty Years a College: Knox College About to Celebrate Its Semi-Centennial|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/28787859/|newspaper=[[Chicago Inter Ocean]]|date=June 4, 1887|p=4|via=Newspapers.com|accessdate=August 11, 2014}} {{open access}}</ref> Knox was the site of the [[Lincoln-Douglas Debates of 1858|fifth debate]] between [[Abraham Lincoln]] and [[Stephen A. Douglas]] in 1858. The [[Old Main (Knox College)|Old Main]] building is the only site from the debates that stands today. Two years after the debates, and during his presidential campaign, Lincoln was awarded the first honorary doctorate ever conferred by Knox College\u2014a [[Doctor of Laws]] degree, announced at the commencement exercises of 5 July 1860.<ref>Muelder, Hermann R. (1959) ''Fighters for Freedom'', Columbia University Press.  {{ISBN|1-58152-409-9}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Academic program===\nKnox employs a 3\u20133 academic calendar rather than a traditional semester-based approach. In each of the three 10-week terms, students take only three courses. Faculty members teach only two courses each term, giving them more time for one-on-one mentoring.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/Academics/3-3-Academic-Calendar.html |title=3-3 Academic Calendar - Knox College |accessdate=2009-02-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217172033/http://www.knox.edu/Academics/3-3-Academic-Calendar.html |archivedate=2009-02-17 }}</ref>\n\nAll courses of study at Knox contain common elements, including an educational plan that students design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/academics/curriculum.html |title=Curriculum - Knox College |accessdate=2009-02-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303021003/http://www.knox.edu/academics/curriculum.html |archivedate=2009-03-03 }}</ref>\n\nKnox College introduced the school's honor code in 1951.<ref name=\"honor system\">{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/Offices-and-Services/Registrar/Catalog/Academic-Program.html |title=The Academic Program |publisher=Knox College |location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |accessdate=2010-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101103043457/http://www.knox.edu/Offices-and-Services/Registrar/Catalog/Academic-Program.html |archive-date=2010-11-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> All students are held responsible for the integrity of their own work, and students are required to abide by the code. Because of this policy, tests are not proctored, and in many cases students may take their exams in any open, public place within the same building. Any cases of students caught disobeying the system are evaluated by their peers through the Honor Board, a [[committee]] consisting of three seniors, three juniors, three sophomores, and three faculty members.\n\nWith the implementation of Renewed Knox, the 2003 curriculum overhaul, the school expanded its academic offerings to meet the needs of a liberal arts education in the 21st century. In 2003, the [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]] awarded the school a $1 million grant to create a new major in [[neuroscience]]; in 2005, the college signed agreements with [[The George Washington University]] to create an early admission program into the university's medical school,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/academics/courses-of-study/medicine/early-admission.html |title=Early Admission Program to Medical School |accessdate=2009-02-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104070935/http://www.knox.edu/academics/courses-of-study/medicine/early-admission.html |archivedate=2009-01-04 }}</ref> and with the [[University of Rochester]] to create a direct admissions program into the university's [[Simon School of Business|Simon School of Business's]] [[MBA]] program;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/Academics/Courses-of-Study/Business-and-Management.html |title=Business and Management |accessdate=2009-02-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091219191546/http://www.knox.edu/Academics/Courses-of-Study/Business-and-Management.html |archivedate=2009-12-19 }}</ref> in 2007 the [[Peace Corps]] launched a new program at Knox, establishing the Peace Corps Preparatory Program, the first of its kind in the country;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/peacecorps.xml |title=Peace Corps Preparatory Program |accessdate=2009-02-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113094559/http://www.knox.edu/peacecorps.xml |archivedate=2009-01-13 }}</ref> Chinese language instruction, Asian Studies, Environmental Studies, and Film Studies were all added;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/academics/courses-of-study.html |title=Courses of Study |accessdate=2009-02-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227030450/http://knox.edu/academics/courses-of-study.html |archivedate=2009-02-27 }}</ref> and new abroad studies programs have been created: the Japan Term,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/japanterm.xml |title=Japan Term |accessdate=2009-02-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208132338/http://www.knox.edu/japanterm.xml |archivedate=2008-12-08 }}</ref> and Knox in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/academics/courses-of-study/art/art-special-programs.html |title=Enhance your Education |accessdate=2009-02-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090723014632/http://www.knox.edu/academics/courses-of-study/art/art-special-programs.html |archivedate=2009-07-23 }}</ref>\n\nKnox is also known for its Green Oaks term, an interdisciplinary program at the {{convert|700|acre|km2 sqmi|adj=on}} Green Oaks Biological Field Station, during which students and faculty spend an entire term conducting research and creative projects and participating in courses in biology, anthropology-sociology, and English, as well as workshops in outdoor skills, first aid, and photography.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/greenoaksterm.xml |title=Green Oaks Term at Knox College |accessdate=2009-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208132333/http://www.knox.edu/greenoaksterm.xml |archivedate=2008-12-08 }}</ref> The Green Field Station began in 1955 under the guidance of zoologist [[Paul Shepard]] and George Ward.<ref>{{cite book|last=Allison|first=Stuart K|title=Ecological Restoration and Environmental Change: Renewing Damaged Ecosystems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bt_fCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA33|date=26 July 2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-46636-6|page=33}}</ref>\n\nKnox also promotes undergraduate research, annually awarding students more than $250,000 in grants to support research and creative projects. Among the programs are the Ford Foundation Research Fellows Program, which funds the scientific, scholarly, and creative projects of 20 students each year, and the summer research program at Knox's Lincoln Studies Center. More than 10 percent of Knox students receive support for independent research and study from the Richter Memorial Foundation Program and the Pew Research Fellowships, which offers Knox students support for off-campus research in science and mathematics. In addition, the Rockefeller Brothers Fund supports student research in ecology and environmental studies and the AAAS/Merck Grant funds interdisciplinary scientific research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/academics/distinctive-programs.html |title=Distinctive Programs |accessdate=2009-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217172043/http://www.knox.edu/Academics/Distinctive-Programs.html |archivedate=2009-02-17 }}</ref>\n\nKnox has many distinctive academic programs. The Honors Program is a year-long, in-depth independent research program in which one in seven seniors participates. It culminates in a major thesis or creative portfolio that is presented to and defended before an honors committee that includes Knox faculty and a specialist from outside the college.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/collegehonors.xml |title=College Honors: Creativity and Independence |accessdate=2009-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113015456/http://www.knox.edu/collegehonors.xml |archivedate=2009-01-13 }}</ref>  In 2007, the [[Andrew W. Mellon Foundation]] awarded Knox a $228,750 grant to create a new Center for Research and Advanced Studies to \"coordinate Knox's numerous existing programs that support advanced work in the natural and social sciences, humanities, and creative and performing arts.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/News-and-Events/News-Archive/Mellon-Grant-for-Research-Center.html |title=Knox Receives Grant for New Campus Research Center &#124; Knox College |publisher=Knox.edu |date=2007-11-27 |accessdate=2010-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100607032855/http://www.knox.edu/News-and-Events/News-Archive/Mellon-Grant-for-Research-Center.html |archive-date=2010-06-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Knox provides a number of combined programs (3 years at Knox, 2\u20133 years at partnering institutions) to offer a few specialized degrees outside of the core liberal arts disciplines. These include engineering ([[Columbia University]], [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]], [[University of Illinois at Urbana Champaign]], [[Washington University in St. Louis]]), environmental management ([[Duke University]]), forestry ([[Duke University]]), occupational therapy ([[Washington University in St. Louis]]), and law ([[University of Chicago]], [[Columbia University]]).\n\nAlmost 50 percent of Knox students take advantage of the opportunities for off-campus learning, studying theatre in [[London]], history in Barcelona, [[French language|French]] immersion in Besan\u00e7on, mathematics in [[Hungary]], social development in [[Tanzania]], language and culture in [[Japan]], political science in [[Washington, D.C.]], and a host of other subjects in Africa, Asia, Europe, Latin America and the United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/offcampusstudy.xml |title=Off-Campus Study |accessdate=2009-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212005125/http://knox.edu/offcampusstudy.xml |archivedate=2009-02-12 }}</ref>\n\n===Faculty===\nThe Knox College faculty is made up of 120 professors, 97 percent of whom hold a Ph.D. or equivalent degree. The student-faculty ratio is 12:1, while the average class size is 17. Prominent faculty members include noted author [[Robert Hellenga]], expert on the relationship between values and well-being [[Tim Kasser]], Middle East expert [[Robert Seibert]], Latin American Expert Karen Kampwirth, Evolutionary Psychologist [[Francis T. McAndrew|Frank McAndrew]], noted expert on 20th-century American art and director of [[The National Center for Midwest Art and Design]] Gregory Gilbert, former Supreme Court Fellow Lane Sunderland, fiction writer [[Chad Simpson (author)]] and co-chairs of the Knox-based Lincoln Studies Center: Rodney Davis and [[Douglas L. Wilson]].\n\n===Lincoln Studies Center===\nThe Lincoln Studies Center was established in 1998 by Rodney Davis and [[Douglas L. Wilson]], who serve as joint co-chairs.  The center deals with issues relating to the life and legacy of [[Abraham Lincoln]] by fostering new research, publishing monographs, hosting annual lectures and occasional symposia.  Students are often employed as assistants in the various projects conducted at the center.  In August 2009, Knox was awarded an $850,000 grant from the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]] \"We the People\" initiative, \"a grant that will provide the base of a permanent endowment for the Center.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/Institutional-Self-Study/Self-Study-Report/Part-4-Resources/13-Human-Resources.html |title=Institutional Self-Study |publisher=Knox College |location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |date= |accessdate=2010-11-27 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Admission==\nAccording to [[The Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching]], Knox is considered to be a more selective institution, with a lower rate of transfer-in students.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://classifications.carnegiefoundation.org/lookup_listings/institution.php |title=Carnegie Classifications &#124; Institution Lookup |work=Carnegie Classifications &#124; Institution Profile |publisher=The Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching |location=Stanford, California |accessdate=2010-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20140511101546/http://classifications.carnegiefoundation.org//lookup_listings//institution.php |archivedate=2014-05-11 }}</ref> For the school year commencing in 2011, more than 3,200 students applied, 1,600 were admitted and 460 chose to enroll.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/Institutional-Self-Study/Self-Study-Report/Appendices/2-Key-Data-and-Statistics-FY1998-through-FY2008.html |title=2009 Institutional Self-Study |publisher=Knox College |location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |year=2009 |accessdate=2010-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091103165719/http://www.knox.edu/Institutional-Self-Study/Self-Study-Report/Appendices/2-Key-Data-and-Statistics-FY1998-through-FY2008.html |archive-date=2009-11-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Of the class commencing in September 2011, 43 percent of students were in the top tenth of their class, 79 percent in the top quarter.  The ACT composite Mid-50 percent Range was 26\u201330, the SAT Mid-50 percent Range 1190\u20131380.<ref name=\"knox-ff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/about-knox/fast-facts.html |title=Fast Facts | publisher = Knox College | location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |accessdate=2012-01-20}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=January 2012}}\n\n===Student body===\n1,420 students were enrolled at Knox in September 2011. These students come from 48 states and territories and 51 countries. Twenty-five percent of U.S. students are of color (7 percent African American, 9 percent Asian American or Pacific Islander, 9 percent Hispanic, 2 percent Native American), and 9 percent are international students.  Women make up 57 percent of the student body, men 43 percent.<ref name=\"knox-ff\"/>\n\n===Financial aid===\nKnox says it is \"committed to ensuring cost is not a barrier to [an] education.\" Over the past seven years, the annual increase in the comprehensive fee has ranged from 3.3 to 5.9%.<ref name=\"knox-cost\">{{cite web | url = http://www.knox.edu/Admission-and-Financial-Aid/Cost-and-Financial-Aid.html | title = Cost and Financial Aid | publisher = Knox College | location = [[Galesburg, Illinois]] | accessdate = 2013-03-29 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130407075710/http://www.knox.edu/Admission-and-Financial-Aid/Cost-and-Financial-Aid.html | archive-date = 2013-04-07 | url-status = dead }}</ref>  A variety of merit-based scholarships (up to full tuition) and need-based financial aid packages are offered. As recently as 2012, both the ''Kiplinger's Personal Finance'' and ''U.S. News & World Report'', named Knox a \"Best Value\" liberal arts college.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/admission-and-financial-aid/why-knox/what-experts-say.html |title=What Experts Say About Knox |publisher=Knox College |location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |date=2013-03-29 |accessdate=2013-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130326041940/http://www.knox.edu/admission-and-financial-aid/why-knox/what-experts-say.html |archive-date=2013-03-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe comprehensive cost (tuition, room, board and fees) of an academic year at Knox was $47,352 in 2013\u20132014.<ref name=\"knox-cost\"/>  U.S. citizens are eligible for a wide array of need- and merit-based scholarships, as well as various federal and private loan programs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/admission-and-financial-aid/cost-and-financial-aid.html |title=Need-based Financial Aid |publisher=Knox College |location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |accessdate=2013-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407075710/http://www.knox.edu/Admission-and-Financial-Aid/Cost-and-Financial-Aid.html |archive-date=2013-04-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> There are numerous avenues for on-campus employment during the academic year. Knox College offers scholarships to qualified international students who wish to take full advantage of what the American liberal arts mode of education has to offer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/Admission-and-Financial-Aid/Cost-and-Financial-Aid/International-Students.html |title=Financial Aid for International Students |publisher=Knox College |location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |accessdate=2013-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717023910/http://www.knox.edu/admission-and-financial-aid/cost-and-financial-aid/international-students.html |archive-date=2012-07-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> International students are also eligible for on-campus jobs.\n\nAccording to the U.S. Department of Education, the median federal debt of Knox College graduates who received student loans was $27,000.  In addition, only 53% of students who attended Knox earned, on average, more than those with only a high school diploma.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collegescorecard.ed.gov/school/?146427-Knox-College|title=U.S. Department of Education|last=|first=|date=|website=College Scorecard|publisher=U.S. Department of Education|access-date=June 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Greek organizations===\nKnox College is home to nine [[Fraternities and sororities in North America|Greek-letter]] organizations, the oldest of which has been on campus since 1855.  Providing a network of alumni to enhance job and life connections, fraternity (men's) and sorority (women's) chapters provide Knox students with living, organizational and learning opportunities. Through their respective inter-Greek governance organizations, chapters conduct a formal recruitment process during each winter term to ensure first-year students have a chance to adjust to college life and classes before joining. Most offer residential housing for members. Some chapters formerly present have closed; of these, alumni members are often still active with the college's alumni association, and recolonization of dormant chapters remains an opportunity for potential new founders.\n\n====Sororities====\nThese organizations are governed by Knox's Panhellenic Council.\n* '''\u0394\u0394\u0394''' [[Delta Delta Delta]], 1889, [[National Panhellenic Conference|NPC]] sorority\n* '''\u03a0\u0392\u03a6''' [[Pi Beta Phi]], 1872, NPC sorority\n* '''\u039a\u039a\u0393''' [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]], 2007, NPC sorority\n* '''\u0391\u03a3\u0391''' [[Alpha Sigma Alpha]], 2010, NPC sorority\n\n====Fraternities====\nThese organizations are governed by Knox's Interfraternity Council .\n* '''\u0392\u0398\u03a0''' [[Beta Theta Pi]], 1855, [[North-American Interfraternity Conference|NIC]] fraternity\n* '''\u039b\u03a7\u0391''' [[Lambda Chi Alpha]], 1915\u20131934, dormant, NIC fraternity\n* '''\u03a6\u0393\u0394''' [[Phi Gamma Delta]] (FIJI), 1867, NIC fraternity\n* '''\u03a3\u039d''' [[Sigma Nu]], 1891, NIC fraternity\n* '''\u03a4\u039a\u0395''' [[Tau Kappa Epsilon]], 1912, NIC fraternity\n* '''\u03a6\u03a3\u039a''' [[Phi Sigma Kappa]], 1928\u20131955, dormant, NIC fraternity\n* '''\u03a3\u03a7''' [[Sigma Chi]], 2007, NIC fraternity\n* '''\u0393\u03d8''' [[Gamma Qoppa]], Gentlemen of Quality, 2007, local organization\n\n===Club activities===\n* Book Club\n* Knox College Business Club\n* Chemistry Club\n* Classics Club\n* Educational Studies Club\n* Equestrian Team\n* French Club\n* German Club\n* Friends of Green Oaks\n* Neuroscience Club\n* Physics Club\n* Pre-Law Club\n* Pre-Health Club\n* Quiz Bowl\n*Knox College Ultimate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theknoxstudent.com/news/2019/04/03/womens-frisbee-victorious-black-penguin/|title=Women\u2019s frisbee victorious at Black Penguin \u2039 The Knox Student|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n===Traditions===\n\nPumphandle is an annual tradition dating back to 1885 during which new members of the community are welcomed to Knox.  On the afternoon before the start of the academic year, all members of the Knox community gather on the south lawn outside Old Main.  The President of the college \"leads the welcoming line, shaking each person's hand in turn. Everyone shakes the hands of those who have gone before, and the line grows, snaking around the campus.\"<ref name=\"knox-traditions\">{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/About-Knox/We-Are-Knox/Our-Traditions.html |title=Our Traditions |publisher=Knox College |location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |accessdate=2010-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103022917/http://www.knox.edu/About-Knox/We-Are-Knox/Our-Traditions.html |archive-date=2011-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFlunk Day is an annual spring carnival that allows students, staff, and faculty to mingle and have fun. Classes are canceled for the day as the student body turns its attention to a joke issue of the student newspaper, live music, inflatable bounce rooms, petting zoos, a mud pit, a paint fight, and a seniors vs faculty softball game. The date of Flunk Day changes every year and is a secret until the entire student body is woken up at around 5am the day of.<ref name=\"knox-traditions\"/> Flunk Day is of particular significance due to the fact that Knox College does not close for reasons other than Winter Break and Spring Break. This one day, Flunk Day, is a time that students, staff, and faculty can all come together.\n\n===Student media===\n* ''The Knox Student'' \u2014 a weekly student newspaper\n* ''Catch'' \u2014 a prize-winning literary magazine\n* ''Cellar Door'' \u2014 a literary magazine\n* ''The Common Room'' \u2014 online journal of literary criticism\n* '' Quiver'' \u2014 a literary magazine of genre fiction\n* ''Folio'' \u2014 a visual arts magazine\n\n''The Knox Student'' has won numerous awards as one of the best college newspapers in the state of the Illinois, including numerous first place \ncategory awards and general excellence awards from the Illinois College Press Association.<ref>{{cite web | title=Awards | website=The Knox Student | url=http://www.theknoxstudent.com/about/awards/ | access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\nKnox's [[radio station]] is [[WVKC]]. It is located on the fourth floor of George Davis Hall, a former science building that now houses the social science and language departments. Its frequency in Galesburg is 90.7. It is ranked #7 in the nation for \"great college radio station\" by the ''[[Princeton Review]]'' in their 2011 ''Best 368 Colleges'' rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spinningindie.blogspot.com/2010/08/princeton-reviews-2011-list-of-most.html |title=Spinning Indie: Princeton Review's 2011 List of \"Most Popular\" College Radio Stations |website=Spinningindie.blogspot.com |date=2010-08-05 |accessdate=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n\n===Athletics===\n[[File:Knox baseball.jpg|thumb|A Knox baseball player at bat in a 1908 game versus [[DePaul University]]]]\nThe current Knox College mascot is the ''Prairie Fire'', a name it adopted in 1993 due to controversy surrounding the former mascot, the ''Old Siwash''. The word ''Siwash'' is rooted in the language of the Chinook Indians of the Pacific Coast of [[Canada]]. It was a derogatory term used by European traders to refer to the local people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billcasselman.com/cwod_archive/siwash_updated.htm |title=Siwash \u2014 Racist Insult Still Proudly Displayed in Vancouver's Stanley Park |first=Bill |last=Casselman |work=Bill Casselman's Canadian Word of the Day |publisher=[[Bill Casselman (mathematician)|Bill Casselman]] |date=2010-06-03 |accessdate=2010-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120125659/http://billcasselman.com/cwod_archive/siwash_updated.htm |archive-date=2010-11-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  The term ''Old Siwash'' was popularized by [[George Helgesen Fitch]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/siwash |title=Siwash &#124; Definition of Siwash by Merriam-Webster |website=Merriam-webster.com |date= |accessdate=2017-03-25}}</ref> (Knox Class of 1897) in his book ''At Good Old Siwash'', and was soon adopted as the school's mascot. However, in 1992 a college publication urged the school to reconsider the name given its pejorative and derogatory implications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stangl|first=Jane M|date=2001|title=Good Old Siwash: A Century of (Mis)appropriation|url=http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/NASSH_Proceedings/NP2001/NP2001zm.pdf|journal=Proceedings & Newsletter - North American Society for Sport History|volume=|pages=52\u201353|issn=0093-6235|oclc=301565562|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402012316/http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/NASSH_Proceedings/NP2001/NP2001zm.pdf|archive-date=2012-04-02}}</ref> The ''Prairie Fire'' refers to the annual spring burning of the prairie lands at Green Oaks. First conducted in the 1950s by Knox professor Paul Shepard, the burn protects prairie grasses from intrusions of woodland scrub and competition with \"exotic\" species that have been introduced to Illinois from other regions or countries\u2014to the detriment of organisms that have evolved over millions of years in delicate balance with the environment and each other.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/x4068.xml |title=Knox College Prairie Burn |accessdate=2009-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080505050545/http://www.knox.edu/x4068.xml |archivedate=2008-05-05 }}</ref>\n\nKnox is a member of the [[Midwest Conference]] of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] at the [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]] level. The school offers 21 men's and women's varsity sports, as well as 11 club sports in such things as water polo, fencing, and [[ultimate frisbee]].  Recent athletic highlights would include the 2016, 2017, & 2018 Conference Champion women's soccer teams that participated in the NCAA Division III National Tournament and the 2018 men's soccer team that did the same. For individual athletes, the outstanding 2016 season of All-American baseball player Drake Sykes, two-time All-American wrestler Jaran Rutledge who placed in the NCAA Division III National Tournament in 2007(3rd) and 2008(8th), and the 2019 sixth-place finish at the NCAA Division III Indoor track national championships of All-American high-jumper Austin Rauch should also be noted.\n\nKnox College is part of the sixth-longest college football rivalry in the United States with [[Monmouth College]].  The Bronze Turkey trophy, awarded annually to the victor of the football game, was created in 1928 and is the brainchild of Knox football alumnus Bill Collins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monm.edu/sportsinfo/bronze-turkey.htm |title=Monmouth College |website=Monm.edu |date=2017-03-21 |accessdate=2017-03-25}}</ref> The Bronze Turkey was named the fifth \"most bizarre college football rivalry trophy\" by ESPN.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/x8428.xml |title=Theatre: At Night's End - Knox College |website=Knox.edu |date=2012-10-30 |accessdate=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:Knox College Seymour Library 2007.jpg|thumb|Seymour Library]]\nKnox College has 45 academic and residential buildings on its {{convert|82|acre|m2|adj=on}} campus.<ref name=\"knox-ff\"/> Knox boasts [[electron microscopes]], a [[Gas-liquid chromatography|gas chromatograph]] [[Mass spectrometry|mass spectrometer]], a [[Celestron]] telescope, access to the Inter University Consortium for Political & Social Research, the Strong Collection of 18th and 19th century maps and photographs, the Hughes Collection of manuscripts and first editions from [[Ernest Hemingway|Hemingway]] and his \"Lost Generation\" contemporaries, and a {{convert|700|acre|km2|adj=on}} natural prairie reserve, the Green Oaks Field Station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewikifire.org/index.php?title=Green_Oaks |title=Green Oaks Biological Field Station |publisher=The Wiki Fire |date=2012-04-22 |accessdate=2017-03-25}}</ref> In 2006, the new E. & L. Andrew Fitness Center was dedicated. The {{convert|13000|sqft|adj=on}}, $2.4-million facility features state-of-the-art equipment, and is significantly larger than the former fitness center, Memorial Gymnasium.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/fitnesscenter.xml |title=E. & L. Andrew Fitness Center |accessdate=2009-02-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104122643/http://www.knox.edu/fitnesscenter.xml |archivedate=2009-01-04 }}</ref>\n\nThe centerpiece of the Knox campus is [[Old Main (Knox College)|Old Main]]. Old Main is \"the oldest building on its campus, and is the best preserved site of one of the 1858 senatorial debates between [[Abraham Lincoln]] and [[Stephen Douglas]].\"  A [[National Historic Landmark]] and part of the [[National Register of Historic Places]].\n\nBuilt in 1928, the Seymour Library was ranked 3rd \"Best Library\" in the nation by the [[Princeton Review]] in 2001. Inside its leaded glass windows and oak paneled reading rooms, the library houses 350,000 books and subscribes to more than 14,000 periodicals.<ref name=\"knox-ff\"/>  Its special collections include the Finley Collection of Midwest History, the Strong Collection of 18th- and 19th-century maps and photographs, the Hughes Collection of manuscripts and first editions from Faulkner, Hemingway and his \"Lost Generation\" contemporaries, and an original [[Encyclop\u00e9die|Diderot Encyclop\u00e9die]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewikifire.org/index.php?title=Diderot_Encyclop%C3%A9die |title=Diderot Encyclop\u00e9die |publisher=The Wiki Fire |date=2007-05-17 |accessdate=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n\nFamous professor and newspaperman [[Christopher Morley]] delivered a three-week-long series of lectures on \"Literature as Companionship\" at Knox in March and April 1938. In one of these lectures, entitled \"Lonely Fun\", he describes the Standish Alcove in the library as modeled after a \"gentleman's library,\" and praised the opportunities the library offered for solitary leisure.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} In addition, Knox offers the Kresge Science & Math Library, which houses the scientific and technical collections of the college,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/Academics/Academic-Facilities/Seymour-Library.html |title=Kresge Science-Mathematics Library |publisher=Knox College |location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |accessdate=2010-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110215230054/http://www.knox.edu/academics/academic-facilities/seymour-library.html |archive-date=2011-02-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=November 2010}} and the Center for the Fine Arts Music Library (CFA), which has collections of compact discs, vinyl record albums, printed music scores, and a core reference collection.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/Academics/Academic-Facilities/Seymour-Library.html |title=Seymour Library |publisher=Knox College |location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |accessdate=2010-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110215230054/http://www.knox.edu/academics/academic-facilities/seymour-library.html |archive-date=2011-02-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFour public [[computer]] laboratories are accessible to students, with several more departmental labs available and a dedicated language laboratory. The largest, Founders Laboratory, is located in Seymour Hall (the [[student activity center|student union]]), and is open 24 hours a day throughout the school year. Scanning (including film-scanning and [[optical character recognition]]) is available freely to student users, and printing and copy services are available for a fee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/Offices-and-Services/Computer-and-Telecommunications-Center/Printing.html |title=Network Printing |publisher=Knox College |location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |accessdate=2010-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110215232312/http://www.knox.edu/offices-and-services/computer-and-telecommunications-center/printing.html |archive-date=2011-02-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In a move to become more environmentally friendly beginning fall of 2005 [[paper recycling|recycled-content paper]] was phased in for use in all college printers, addressing the issues of paper waste.\n\nIn 2002, a major curriculum revision entitled \"Renewed Knox\" was launched. With this revision came the creation of six new academic centers: The Center for Research and Advanced Studies, The Center for Global Studies, The Center for Career and Pre-Professional Development, The Center for Community Service, The Center for Teaching and Learning, and The Center for Intercultural Life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/Offices-and-Services/Office-of-the-President/2008-Presidents-Report/Six-Centers-of-Learning.html |title=Six Centers of Learning |accessdate=2010-07-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330213637/http://www.knox.edu/Offices-and-Services/Office-of-the-President/2008-Presidents-Report/Six-Centers-of-Learning.html |archivedate=2010-03-30 }}</ref>\n\nStudents established the Knox College Community Garden in 2007 as an independent study project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theknoxstudent.com/newsroom/article/independent-study-goes-organic/ |title=Independent study goes organic |first=Sadie |last=Arft |work=The Knox Student |publisher=Knox College |location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |date=2008-04-08 |accessdate=2010-11-27}}</ref>  It continues to be tended by student volunteers, and produces a variety of annual and perennial vegetables and flowers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/Student-Life/Organizations-and-Clubs/Knox-Community-Garden.html |title=Knox Community Garden |publisher=Knox College |location=[[Galesburg, Illinois]] |accessdate=2010-11-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110217020611/http://www.knox.edu/student-life/organizations-and-clubs/knox-community-garden.html |archive-date=2011-02-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== U.S. Department of Education College Scorecard ==\nAccording to the U.S. Department of Education, 18% of students who started college at Knox College later transferred to another school.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://collegescorecard.ed.gov/school/?146427-Knox-College|title=School {{!}} College Scorecard|website=collegescorecard.ed.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> 16% of the entering class did not return after their first year.<ref name=\":0\" /> Although African Americans make up 13.4% of the U.S. population, African Americans only make up 8% of the Knox College student body.<ref name=\":0\" /> Graduates of Knox College typically earn between $18,300 and $33,100 which is significantly lower than the average starting salary paid to college graduates of about $50,000.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Recent commencement speakers==\n[[File:Stephen Colbert December 2017.jpg|thumb|[[Stephen Colbert]], 2006 commencement speaker, in 2017]]\n\nRecently, Knox has had several well-known commencement speakers, including [[Barack Obama]] (2005), [[Stephen Colbert]] (2006), [[Bill Clinton]] (2007), [[Madeleine Albright]] (2008), [[Patrick J. Fitzgerald]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Daniel Libit |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/04/us/04cncknox.html |title=Tiny Knox College Stands Tall at Commencements |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2010-04-03 |accessdate=2017-03-25}}</ref> (2009), [[Christina Tchen]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Tina Tchen Delivers Commencement Address at Knox College | website=whitehouse.gov | date=2010-06-09 | url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/blog/2010/06/09/tina-tchen-delivers-commencement-address-knox-college | access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref> (2010), [[Majora Carter]] (2011), [[Ed Helms]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.galesburg.com/newsnow/x1522322601/Actor-comedian-Ed-Helms-to-give-Knox-College-commencement-address|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130411001032/http://www.galesburg.com/newsnow/x1522322601/Actor-comedian-Ed-Helms-to-give-Knox-College-commencement-address|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 11, 2013|newspaper=Galesburg Register-Mail|title=Actor, comedian Ed Helms to give Knox College commencement address|date=February 13, 2013|accessdate=February 13, 2013}}</ref> (2013), [[Eva Longoria]] (2017) and [[Vir Das]] (2018).\n\n==Alumni==\nKnox College has over 15,000 living alumni on all seven continents.  The alumni giving rate was equal to 36.4% (the highest rate among liberal arts colleges in Illinois) in the 2008\u20132009 giving year, with more than 5,500 individuals contributing to the college.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.knox.edu/Give-to-Knox/Giving-Societies/Honor-Roll-of-Donors-2009.html |title=Honor Roll of Donors 2009 |accessdate=2010-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301213302/http://www.knox.edu/Give-to-Knox/Giving-Societies/Honor-Roll-of-Donors-2009.html |archivedate=2010-03-01 }}</ref>  According to the 2009 Institutional Self-Study, Knox prepares its graduates well for life after graduation.  80 percent of those wishing to attend medical school were accepted (the national average was 50 percent), while 90 percent of students who worked with the pre-law advisor were admitted to one or more law schools.<ref name=\"knox-ssr\">{{cite web |url=http://www.knox.edu/Institutional-Self-Study/Self-Study-Report.html |title=Institutional Self-Study - Knox College |website=Knox.edu |accessdate=2017-03-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091103165653/http://www.knox.edu/Institutional-Self-Study/Self-Study-Report.html |archive-date=2009-11-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Knox is also in the top 3 percent of schools whose graduates attain a Ph.D.<ref name=\"knox-self-2009-9\">{{cite web | url = http://www.knox.edu/2009-Institutional-Self-Study/Self-Study-Report/Part-2-Carrying-Out-the-Mission/9-The-Impact-of-a-Knox-Education.html | work = Institutional Self-Study Report, 2009 | year = 2009 | title = Chapter 9: The Impact of a Knox Education | page = 140 | publisher = Knox College | location = [[Galesburg, Illinois]] | accessdate = 2010-04-28 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100610035227/http://www.knox.edu/2009-Institutional-Self-Study/Self-Study-Report/Part-2-Carrying-Out-the-Mission/9-The-Impact-of-a-Knox-Education.html | archive-date = 2010-06-10 | url-status = dead }}</ref>  In the decade ending in 2009, 15 Knox alumni have been awarded the prestigious [[Fulbright]] Scholarship for foreign study.<ref name=\"knox-ssr\"/>\n\n===Notable alumni===\n<!-- DO NOT ADD PEOPLE TO THIS LIST WITHOUT A VERIFIABLE CITATION.\nAdditions without a citation are subject to removal. \nIf a citation link is broken, please replace it with one that works.\n-->\n*  [[Edgar Bancroft|Edgar Addison Bancroft]] \u2014 lawyer and diplomat, served as United States Ambassador to Japan 1924\u20131925\n* [[Barry Bearak]] 1971 \u2014 ''New York Times'' journalist and visiting professor at [[Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism]], winner of 2002 [[Pulitzer Prize for International Reporting]]<ref>{{cite news|url= http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/barry_bearak/index.html|title= Barry Bearak|newspaper= New York Times|accessdate= January 5, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Matt Berg]] 2000 \u2014 CEO of Ona, former director of ICT for Millennium Villages Project at [[Columbia University]]'s [[Earth Institute]]; named in 2010 as one of the [[Time 100]] Most Influential People of the World<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.knox.edu/news/news-archive/time-magazine-names-knox-graduate-to-100-most-influential-leaders|title= Time magazine - Knox grad is among 100 \"most influential people in the world\"|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Earnest Elmo Calkins]] 1891 \u2014 founder of first modern advertising agency<ref>{{cite web|url= http://library.knox.edu/archives/manuscripts/calkins7.htm|title= Earnest Elmo Calkins/Willis E. Terry Letters Manuscript Collection|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 5, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Amy Carlson]] 1990 \u2014 actress, known for [[NBC]] television series ''[[Third Watch]],'' the [[CBS]] series \"[[Blue Bloods (TV series)|Blue Bloods]],\"and ''[[Law & Order: Trial by Jury]]''<ref>{{cite web|url= http://departments.knox.edu/newsarchive/news_events/2003/x5982.html|title= Actress Amy Carlson|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 5, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Job Adams Cooper]] 1867 \u2014 [[List of Governors of Colorado|Sixth Governor]] of [[State of Colorado]], 1889\u20131891<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.nga.org/cms/home/governors/past-governors-bios/page_colorado/col2-content/main-content-list/title_cooper_job.html|title= Colorado Governor Job Adams Cooper|publisher= National Governors Association |accessdate= September 25, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Vir Das]] 2004 \u2014 comedian, [[Bollywood actor]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.knox.edu/news/news-archive/knox-college-graduate-bollywood-star-vir-das-us-tour|title= Rave Reviews for U.S. Comedy Debut of Knox Grad Vir Das|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 5, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Charles Eastman]] \u2014 Native American physician, activist and Boy Scout official<ref>{{cite web|url= http://publications.newberry.org/frontiertoheartland/items/show/164|title= Charles A. Eastman at Knox College in 1880|publisher= The Newberry Library Chicago|accessdate= January 5, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Ethyl Eichelberger]] \u2014 born James Roy Eichelberger, a famous [[drag queen]], playwright and actor, for whom a prize was founded by downtown Manhattan theatre institution [[P.S. 122]]<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1990/08/14/obituaries/ethyl-eichelberger-performer-45-creator-of-a-gallery-of-characters.html|title= Ethyl Eichelberger, Performer, 45; Creator of a Gallery of Characters|newspaper= New York Times|accessdate= January 5, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Bill Essick]] \u2014 former pitcher for [[Cincinnati Reds]], baseball executive and scout<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/e/essicbi01.shtml|title= Bill Essick|publisher= BaseballReference.com|accessdate= January 1, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Fred Ewing]] 1913 \u2014 physician, sixth head football coach of [[University of Oklahoma]] and first to require academically eligible players<ref>{{cite web|url= http://blog.knox.edu/knoxinthenews/?p=334|title= Tom Wilson: Galesburg Doctor Played Football At Knox|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 5, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Eugene Field]] \u2014 poet, journalist, and author<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.knox.edu/library/special-collections-and-archives/rare-books/eugene-field-collection|title= The Eugene Field Collection|publisher= Knox.edu|accessdate= January 5, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[John Huston Finley]] 1887 \u2014 author, former president of Knox College,  president of [[City College of New York]], associate editor of ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.knox.edu/library/special-collections-and-archives/rare-books/finley-collection|title= The Finley Collection|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Jack Finney]] 1934 \u2014 science-fiction author, works include ''[[The Body Snatchers]]'' and ''[[Time and Again (Finney novel)|Time and Again]]''<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.writing.upenn.edu/~afilreis/50s/finney-obit.html|title= Jack Finney, 84, Sci-Fi Author Of Time-Travel Tales, Dies|newspaper= New York Times|accessdate= January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[George Helgesen Fitch]] 1897 \u2014 author, journalist, and humorist<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0280006/|title= George Fitch|publisher= IMBD.com|accessdate= January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[David P. Fridovich]] 1974 \u2014 retired [[Lieutenant General]] and [[Special Forces (United States Army)|Green Beret]] in [[United States Army|U.S. Army]], former Deputy Commander of U.S. military's [[United States Special Operations Command]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.knox.edu/fridovich-david-74|title= David Fridovich '74|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Hobart R. Gay]] 1917 \u2014 [[U.S. Army]] general, served under General [[George S. Patton]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://library.knox.edu/archives/manuscripts/hobart_gay.htm|title= Hobart R. Gay Manuscript Collection|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Robert Hanssen]] 1966 \u2014 [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] agent convicted of spying for [[Soviet Union]] and [[Russia]] in 2001, subject of film ''[[Breach (film)|Breach]]'' (2007)<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url= http://www.britannica.com/biography/Robert-Hanssen|title= Robert Hanssen: American law enforcement agent and spy|encyclopedia= Encyclopaedia Britannica|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Otto Harbach]] 1895 \u2014 songwriter for whom Knox's Harbach Theater is named<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/exhibits/bio/C105|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090109134637/http://www.songwritershalloffame.org/exhibits/bio/C105|url-status= dead|archive-date= January 9, 2009|title= Otto Harbach Biography|publisher= Songwriters Hall of Fame|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Don Harmon]] 1988 \u2014 Illinois State Senator (Democrat) and Senate President Pro Tempore\n*[[Loyal M. Haynes]] 1918 \u2014 [[Brigadier General]] in [[United States Army|U.S. Army]], commanding general of 2nd Division Artillery Unit in Korean War and survivor of the [[1946 C-53 Skytrooper crash on the Gauli Glacier]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k8d2YX43hMoC&pg=PA236|title= Disaster in Korea: The Chinese Confront MacArthur|publisher= Roy E. Appleman|accessdate= June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=YipJAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA111|title= Knox College Catalog|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= June 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.thehistoryblog.com/archives/18829|title= Teens find famed 1946 plane wreck in Swiss glacier|publisher= The History Blog|accessdate= August 20, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171103004657/http://www.thehistoryblog.com/archives/18829|archive-date= 2017-11-03|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n* [[B. J. Hollars]] 2007 \u2014 author\n* [[Bob Jamieson]]  \u2014 [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] news correspondent<ref>{{cite web|url= http://departments.knox.edu/newsarchive/news_events/2003/x3517.html|title= Bob Jamieson at Knox Talks, Feb. 11|publisher= Knox College|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Frank J. Jirka, Jr.]] 1944 \u2014 former president of [[American Medical Association]]<ref>{{cite news|url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2000-10-04/news/0010040176_1_ama-trustee-illinois-state-medical-society-macneal-hospital|title= Dr. Frank J. Jirka Jr., Ex-ama President|newspaper= Chicago Tribune|accessdate= January 7, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Whitcomb Judson]]  \u2014 inventor of the [[zipper]]<ref>{{cite web|url= http://historyofscience2009.blogspot.com/2009/03/whitcomb-l-judson-zipper.html|title= Whitcomb L. Judson- Zipper|publisher= historyofscience2009.blogspot.com|accessdate= January 7, 2016|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151218150531/http://historyofscience2009.blogspot.com/2009/03/whitcomb-l-j