uth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:FC Dynamo Moscow reserves players]]\n[[Category:FC Luch Vladivostok players]]\n[[Category:Russian Premier League players]]\n[[Category:FC Torpedo Moscow players]]\n[[Category:FC SKA-Khabarovsk players]]\n[[Category:FC Oryol players]]\n[[Category:FC Lokomotiv Moscow players]]\n[[Category:Saif Sporting Club players]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Football Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Bangladesh]]\n\n{{Russia-footy-midfielder-1987-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update FootballFacts.ru template, misc formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denis_Bolshakov"}
{"title_page": "University of Alabama at Birmingham", "text_new": "{{redirect|UAB|Universitat Aut\u00f2noma de Barcelona|Autonomous University of Barcelona|other uses}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name           = The University of Alabama at Birmingham\n|image          = University of Alabama at Birmingham seal.png\n|image_upright  = .7\n|established    = 1969\n|type           = [[Public university|Public]]\n|endowment      = $495.3 million <ref>{{cite web|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/uab-1052 |title=University of Alabama-Birmingham &#124; UAB &#124; Best College &#124; US News |publisher=Colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-25}}</ref>\n|president      = [[Ray L. Watts]]\n|provost        = Pam Benoit\n|city           = [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]]\n|state          = [[Alabama]]\n|country        = United States\n|students       = 21,923\n|undergrad      = 13,836\n|postgrad       = 8,087\n|faculty        = 2,605 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/facstaff/2018-UAB_workforce.pdf|title=UAB Work Force|accessdate=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n|coor           = {{coord|33.500000|-86.807500|type:city_region:US|display=inline}}\n|colors         = Green & White & Gold <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uab.edu/brand/home/standards/colors |title=UAB - Brand Toolkit - Colors |publisher=Uab.edu |accessdate=2016-03-25}}</ref><br />{{color box|#1E6B52}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n|nickname       = [[UAB Blazers|Blazers]]\n|mascot         = Blaze the [[Dragon]]\n|affiliations   = [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]], [[Great Cities' Universities]], [[University of Alabama System]]\n|sports         = 17 Intercollegiate Sports ([[NCAA]] [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] \u2013 [[Conference USA]])\n|website        = {{URL|www.uab.edu}}\n|logo           = UABirmingham logo.png\n|logo_upright   = 1.2\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Alabama at Birmingham''' ('''UAB''') is a [[Public university#United States|public]] [[List of research universities in the United States|research university]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama]]. Developed from an academic extension center established in 1936, the institution became a four-year campus in 1966 and a fully autonomous university in [[University of Alabama System|the University of Alabama System]] in 1969.\n\nUAB offers 140 programs of study in 12 academic divisions leading to [[bachelor's degree|bachelor's]], [[master's degree|master's]], [[doctorate|doctoral]], and [[professional degree|professional]] degrees in the [[social sciences|social]] and [[behavioral sciences]], the [[liberal arts]], [[business]], [[education]], [[engineering]], and health-related fields such as medicine, dentistry, optometry, nursing, and public health.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uasystem.edu//wp-content/uploads/2017/02/UAB-Financial-Report-Final.pdf|title=UAB 2016 Financial Report|work=University of Alabama at Birmingham|accessdate=23 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224131434/http://uasystem.edu//wp-content/uploads/2017/02/UAB-Financial-Report-Final.pdf|archive-date=2017-02-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the fall of 2018, 21,923 students from more than 110 countries were enrolled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/student-data/headcount-enrollment|title=UAB \u2013 Institutional Effectiveness and Analysis- Student Data Headcount Enrollment Report|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe UAB Health System, one of the largest [[academic medical center]]s in the United States, is affiliated with the university. [[UAB Hospital]] sponsors residency programs in medical specialties, including [[internal medicine]], neurology, physical medicine and rehabilitation, surgery, [[radiology]], and [[anesthesiology]]. UAB Hospital is the only [[Level I trauma center]] in Alabama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facs.org/trauma/verified.html|title=Trauma Centers|work=American College of Surgeons|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nUAB is the state's largest single employer, with more than 23,000 faculty and staff and over 53,000 jobs at the university and in the health system. An estimated 10 percent of the jobs in the [[Birmingham-Hoover Metropolitan Area]] and 1 in 31 jobs in the state of Alabama are directly or indirectly related to UAB. The university's overall annual economic impact was estimated to be $7.15 billion in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/impact/|title=UAB \u2013 How UAB powers Alabama's Economy - UAB Annual Impact on the Alabama Economy|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2017/10/uab_generates_715_billion_econ.html|title=UAB creates $7.15 billion in economic impact, study shows|author=Erin Edgemon|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{| style=\"float:right; margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 0.5em; width:20em; border:1px solid #a0a0a0; text-align:center; line-height:12px; font-size:x-small;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center; line-height:16px; font-size:small;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"color:white; background:#1E6B52;\"| Presidents of UAB\n|-\n| Dr. Joseph F. Volker\n| 1966\u20131976 (titled as VP for Birmingham Affairs, 1966-1969)<ref name=\"Chronology\"/>\n|-\n| Dr. S. Richardson Hill Jr.\n| 1977\u20131987\n|-\n| Dr. Charles A. McCallum\n| 1987\u20131993\n|-\n| Dr. J. Claude Bennett\n| 1993\u20131996\n|-\n| Mr. Paul Hardin\n| 1997 (Interim)\n|-\n| [[W. Ann Reynolds|Dr. W. Ann Reynolds]]\n| 1997\u20132002\n|-\n| [[Carol Garrison|Dr. Carol Z. Garrison]]\n| 2002\u20132012\n|-\n| [[Ray L. Watts|Dr. Ray L. Watts]]\n| 2013\u2013present\n|}\n\nIn 1936, in response to the rapid growth of the Birmingham metropolitan area and the need for the population to have access to a university education, the [[University of Alabama]] in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]] established the '''Birmingham Extension Center'''.<ref name=\"Chronology\">{{cite web |title=UAB Chronology |url=http://library.uab.edu/locations/archives/uab-history |accessdate=May 29, 2011}}</ref>  The center operated in an old house in downtown Birmingham at 2131 6th Avenue North and enrolled 116 students. In 1945, UA's newly established four-year [[University of Alabama School of Medicine|School of Medicine]] moved from Tuscaloosa to Birmingham and took over management of Jefferson and Hillman hospitals. In 1957 enrollment at the extension center stood at 1,856. By 1959, research grants, training grants, and fellowships exceeded $1 million, and ground was broken for a new Children's Hospital.\n\nBy the 1960s, it grew apparent that the extension center was becoming a university in its own right. An engineering building was built close to the medical center in 1962, and in November 1966, the Extension Center and the School of Medicine were merged into the '''University of Alabama in Birmingham''', with Dr. Joseph Volker as \"Vice President for Birmingham Affairs\"\u2013reflecting that it was still treated as an offsite department of the main campus in Tuscaloosa. An Advisory Board for UAB was created in 1967. In 1969, the legislature created the [[University of Alabama System]]. UAB became one of three four-year institutions within the new system, which also included UA and the [[University of Alabama in Huntsville]] (UAH) in [[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]].  Volker became UAB's first president.<ref name=\"Chronology\"/>\n\nIn the 1970s, the university began a period of rapid growth. Enrollment at the beginning of the decade stood at 6,629, including 2,724 women. To accommodate the growing student population, UAB acquired land in the [[Southside (Birmingham)|Southside]]. UAB Mini Park (the predecessor to The UAB Green) was dedicated in 1977.\n\nThe university created an intercollegiate athletic program, joined the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] and began fielding teams beginning with golf in 1970 and men's basketball in 1978. The university's name was changed to the '''University of Alabama at Birmingham''' in 1984, simply exchanging the preposition \"In\" for \"at.\"\n\nBy 1990, UAB had awarded its 50,000th degree. In 1992, ''U.S. News and World Report'' named UAB as the #1 up-and-coming university in the United States. In 1993, UAB's economic impact on the Birmingham region was estimated at more than $1.5 billion per year (the figure would be $2 billion per year by 1998). In 1994, UAB became the first Alabama university to achieve \"Research University I\" status in the [[List of research universities in the United States|Carnegie Foundation classification]].\n\n== Campus ==\n[[File:University of Alabama at Birmingham Campus from Vulcan.jpg|thumb|upright=2.5|right|UAB campus and downtown Birmingham]]\nUAB is located in the [[Southside (Birmingham)|Southside]] neighborhood of downtown Birmingham. Occupying more than 100 city blocks,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://alabamanewscenter.com/2018/06/06/uab-ranked-no-1-young-university-u-s/|title=UAB ranked No. 1 young university in the U.S.|author=Tyler Greer|accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref> the roughly rectangular campus blends with the urban character of the Southside, stretching between 4th Ave S and 12th Ave S north to south and 8th St and 22nd St east to west. University Boulevard serves as the main axis of the rectangle and Campus Green sits approximately at the center.\n\nThe campus can be divided into three sections. The medical center occupies most of the campus east of Campus Green. The medical center is home to the health science schools and their teaching facilities, including the UAB Health System (UABHS). The medical center overlaps with the larger Birmingham Medical District where, in addition to UABHS, non-UAB affiliated hospitals such as the VA Medical Center Birmingham, Children's Hospital of Alabama and Cooper Green Mercy Hospital are located.\n\nThe academic heart of campus stretches from the Campus Green west and from University Boulevard south. Campus Green, developed between 2000 and 2007 as part of the move to convert the school from its previously commuter school feel into a more traditional residential campus, not only anchors the academic campus but serves as the centerpiece for the university as a whole. Most academics and arts buildings (excluding those associated with the medical center), residence halls, and student life facilities sit on or within two blocks of the Green.\n[[File:CAMPUS GREEN.jpg|thumb|Students relaxing on Campus Green]]\n\nAthletics facilities, including [[Bartow Arena]], are located on the far western side of campus.\n\nSince 1969, UAB has undergone extensive growth and construction projects are common across campus. Projects that are in planning, recently completed, or under construction include:<ref name=\"UAB President's Annual Report: 2019\">{{cite report |title=UAB Presdient's Annual Report New Kids on the Block|url=https://www.uab.edu/president/report|access-date=April 12, 2019}}</ref>\n* Collat School of Business and Bill L. Harbert Institute for Innovation and Entrepreneurship, ribbon cutting on August 28, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/erry-2018/08/e57ca0fc4d5292/tour-the-new-uab-collat-school.html|title=Tour the new UAB Collat School of Business opening today|author=Joe Songer|accessdate= 27 August 2018}}</ref>\n* Police and Public Safety Headquarters, ribbon cutting on August 9, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/news/campus/item/9664-new-uab-police-and-public-safety-headquarters-is-now-open|title=New UAB Police and Public Safety headquarters is now open|author=Tiffany Westry|accessdate= 9 August 2018}}</ref>\n* School of Nursing, ribbon cutting on September 6, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbrc.com/2018/09/06/uab-unveiling-new-state-of-the-art-building-school-nursing/|title=UAB unveiling new state-of-the-art building for School of Nursing|author=Shilo Groover|accessdate= 27 August 2018}}</ref>\n* College of Arts & Sciences University Hall - the first LEED-certified building on UAB campus - ribbon cutting on September, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.gmcnetwork.com/news/2019/09/uab-opens-its-first-leed-certified-building-on-campus/|title=UAB opens its first LEED-certified building on campus|author=GMC Network|accessdate= 4 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Organization and administration ==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:90%; line-height:1.4em; width:300px;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''Academic Divisions of UAB'''\n|-\n| '''College/school''' || '''Year founded<ref name=\"fact-book\">{{cite report|url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/factbook/FactsFigures2016-2017.pdf|title=Facts & Figures 2016-2017|last=|first=|date=March 2017|publisher=University of Alabama at Birmingham|issue=|doi=|volume=|pmid=|accessdate=June 19, 2018}}</ref>'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |<hr />\n|-\n| College of Arts and Sciences || 2010\n|-\n| School of Business || 1971\n|-\n| School of Dentistry || 1945\n|-\n| School of Education || 1971\n|-\n| School of Engineering || 1971\n|-\n| School of Health Professions || 1969\n|-\n| School of Medicine || 1945\n|-\n| School of Nursing || 1967\n|-\n| School of Optometry || 1969\n|-\n| School of Public Health || 1981\n|-\n| Honors College || 2012\n|-\n| Graduate School || 1970\n|}\n\nUAB is an autonomous institution within the [[University of Alabama System]], which is governed by the Board of Trustees of the University of Alabama and headed by Chancellor of the University of Alabama. The board is self-nominating and composed of 15 elected members and two [[ex officio]] members. The makeup of the board is dictated by the [[Constitution of Alabama|Constitution of the State of Alabama]], and requires that the board be made up of three members from the [[congressional district]] that contains the Tuscaloosa campus, and two members from every other congressional district in Alabama. Board members are elected by the board and are confirmed by the [[Alabama Senate|Alabama State Senate]]. Board members may serve three consecutive six-year terms.<ref name=\"board\">{{cite web |title=The Board of Trustees of The University of Alabama, History and Purpose |url=http://www.uasystem.ua.edu/board/Board%20history.htm |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515231429/http://www.uasystem.ua.edu/board/Board%20history.htm |archivedate=May 15, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe president of the University of Alabama at Birmingham is the principal executive officer of the university and is appointed by the chancellor with approval of the Board of Trustees. The president reports directly to the chancellor, and is responsible for the daily operations of the university. The president also acts as chairman of the board of the UAB Health System.<ref>{{cite web |title=UAB Medicine Leadership |url=http://www.uabmedicine.org/about-us/about-us-leadership |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref> Richard Marchase was named interim president on August 21, 2012, after the retirement of former president [[Carol Garrison]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Richard Marchase named interim president of UAB |url=http://www.uab.edu/news/latest/item/2671-dr-richard-marchase-named-interim-president-of-uab |date=August 21, 2012 |accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Richard Marchase, veteran administrator, named interim president of the University of Alabama at Birmingham |url=http://blog.al.com/spotnews/2012/08/richard_marchese_veteran_admin.html |date=August 21, 2012 |accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=UAB's Carol Garrison to step down after decade as president |url=http://www.uab.edu/news/latest/item/2658-uabs-carol-garrison-to-step-down-after-decade-as-president |date=August 16, 2012 |accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title =UAB President Carol Garrison stepping down after 10 years |url=http://blog.al.com/spotnews/2012/08/uab_president_carol_garrison_s_1.html |date=August 16, 2012 |accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref> In February 2013, Ray L. Watts became UAB's seventh president.<ref>{{cite web|title = Ray Watts name new president of UAB| url=https://www.bizjournals.com/birmingham/news/2013/02/08/ray-watts-named-new-president-of-uab.html|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Colleges ===\nUAB is composed of one college, nine schools and the Graduate School. Together, these divisions offer 56 bachelor's degree programs, 59 master's degree programs, and 40 doctoral programs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/factbook/sections/52-54_FactsFigures2018_DegreesOfferedAtUAB.pdf|title=Degrees Offered at UAB, Student Information|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\nBefore 2010, the schools of Arts and Humanities, Social and Behavioral Sciences, Natural Science and Mathematics, and Education were separate, degree-granting units within the university. The schools were merged into a single college (the first at UAB): the College of Arts and Sciences, with Education retaining its identity as a distinct unit within the new college. University leaders cited efficiency, curricula, and more opportunity for interdisciplinary research and cooperation for the restructuring.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://main.uab.edu/Sites/MediaRelations/articles/70134/ |title=UAB Announces Realignment; Forming a College of Arts & Sciences |access-date=2011-05-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925151320/http://main.uab.edu/Sites/MediaRelations/articles/70134/ |archive-date=2011-09-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Endowment ===\nUAB's endowment stood at $495.3 million in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/uab-1052 |title=University of Alabama-Birmingham &#124; UAB &#124; Best College &#124; US News |publisher=Colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2019-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, the university launched a capital campaign with a goal of $250 million. When it ended in 2003, the UAB Capital Campaign had raised over $388.7 million.\n\nThe Campaign for UAB launched publicly in October 2013 with a goal of raising $1 billion. Prior to the public launch of the campaign, UAB had already received over $420 million in donations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uab.edu/give/campaign/foruab|title=UAB \u2013 The Campaign for UAB \u2013 The Campaign for UAB|author=Linda Gunter|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref> In 2018, UAB exceeded the $1 billion goal of The Campaign for UAB, the most ambitious fundraising effort in the university\u2019s history. Putting the Campaign over its goal was the largest single gift ever made to UAB:  $30 million from O\u2019Neal Industries and its shareholders to name the O\u2019Neal Comprehensive Cancer Center at UAB.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/news/campus/item/9987-thanks-a-billion-the-campaign-for-uab-surpasses-1-billion|title=UAB \u2013 UAB News \u2013 Thanks a billion: The Campaign for UAB surpasses $1 billion|author=Tyler Greer|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/news/health/item/10005-o-neal-industries-gift-will-leverage-advances-in-cancer-research-patient-care-and-biotechnology-growth  |title=UAB \u2013 UAB News\u2013 O'Neal Industries gift will leverage advances in cancer research, patient care and biotechnology growth|author=Jeff Hansen|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Academics ==\n{| style=\"text-align:center; float:right;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Average tuition for full-time students (AY 2013\u20132014)<ref name=\"tuition\">{{cite web |title=2013-2014: Tuition Summary, University of Alabama at Birmingham| url=https://www.uab.edu/students/current/paying-for-college/detailed-tuition-and-fees |accessdate= March 5, 2014}}</ref>\n! - !! Alabama resident !! Non-resident\n|-\n| Undergraduate (2 x 15cr) || $8,904|| $20,394\n|-\n| Graduate (2 x 12cr)|| $8,934 || $20,454\n|-\n| Optometry (yr)|| $8,045 || $17,140\n|-\n| Dentistry (yr)|| $11,861 || $27,380\n|-\n| Medicine (yr)|| $24,510 || $58,590\n|}\n\nUAB is a large, four-year primarily non-residential research university.<ref name=\"Carnegie1\">{{cite web |title=Carnegie Classifications \u2013 University of Alabama at Birmingham |url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=100663 |publisher=Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching |accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref> UAB has been accredited by the [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]] since 1970, according to the [[United States Department of Education|U.S. Department of Education]].<ref name=\"USDOE\">{{cite web |title=College Navigator \u2013 University of Alabama at Birmingham |url=http://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=University+of+Alabama+at+Birmingham&s=all&id=100663 |publisher=National Center for Education Statistics, United States Department of Education Institute for Education Sciences |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>  Undergraduates comprise a majority of the total university enrollment. Part-time and transfer student comprise a sizable portion of the undergraduate student body. The undergraduate instructional program provides a balance between professional programs of study and the liberal arts (meaning the number of degrees awarded in the two areas is similar), and there is a high level of co-existence between the graduate and undergraduate programs (meaning that the majority of undergraduate program have graduate degree program counterparts). The university has a high level of research activity and has a graduate instructional program emphasizing doctorates in [[STEM fields]] as well as  professional programs in the health and veterinary sciences. UAB is one of only 108 universities in the country (and one of only two in Alabama) with the \"very high level\" research rating.<ref name=\"carnegie2\">{{cite web |title= Carnegie Classifications \u2013 Standard Listings |url=http://classifications.carnegiefoundation.org/lookup_listings/srp.php?clq={%22basic2005_ids%22%3A%2215%22}|accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe academic calendar is based on the [[semester#United States|semester system]], which divides the [[academic year#Academic year|academic year]], lasting from mid-August to early May, into two 15-week semesters (fall and spring) and the summer. The fall semester ends in early December and the spring term begins in early January. The summer, which lasts from mid-May to August, is divided into a number of sessions: a 12-week session, a 3-week \"mini-semester\" in May, a nine-week session in June and July, and two four-week sessions in June and July, respectively.<ref name=\"academic-calender\">{{cite web |title=Academic Calendar |url=http://main.uab.edu/Sites/students/services/registration/48843/ |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713115606/http://main.uab.edu/Sites/students/services/registration/48843/ |archive-date=July 13, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The schools of medicine and dentistry follow an academic calendar beginning in July and ending in late May/early June.<ref name=\"medschool-calendar\">{{cite web |title=Academic Year Term Dates, UAB School of Medicine |url=http://medicine.uab.edu/education/62006/ |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"dentalschool-calender\">{{cite web |title=Academic Calendar, School of Dentistry |url=http://www.dental.uab.edu/students/current-students/academic-calendar1.html |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn academic year 2016\u20132017, UAB awarded a total 2,384 bachelor's degrees; 1,795 master's degrees, 33 educational specialist degrees; 125 research doctorates; and 391 professional doctorates.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/factbook/FactsFigures2017-2018.pdf/|title=UAB \u20132017-2018 Facts & Figures|accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Student profile ===\nIn fall semester 2018, the UAB student body consisted of 13,836 undergraduates, 6,933 graduate students and 1,154 professional doctoral students from all 67 Alabama counties, all 50 states and more than 110 foreign countries. In fall semester 2018, 5,737 students were enrolled in the College of Arts and Sciences, 1,775 in Education, 3,432 in Business, 271 in Dentistry, 1,486 in Engineering, 2,431 in Health Professions, 324 in Joint Health Sciences, 694 in Medicine, 2,736 in Nursing, 217 in Optometry, 752 in Public Health, while 1,902 were undecided.\n\nOf the undergraduate student body, 33.2% are from [[Jefferson County, Alabama|Jefferson County]], 14.4% are from other counties in the [[Birmingham\u2013Hoover Metropolitan Area|Birmingham metropolitan area]], specifically [[Blount County, Alabama|Blount]], [[Shelby County, Alabama|Shelby]], [[St. Clair County, Alabama|St. Clair]] and [[Walker County, Alabama|Walker]] counties. 29.4% come from the rest of Alabama, 18.2% from the rest of the United States, while international students comprise 4.8%. The male-to-female ratio among undergraduates is 2:3. Reflecting one of the core reasons for UAB's founding, a large percentage of undergraduates are from non-traditional demographics. 27.4% of undergraduates are part-time students, and 18.7% are above the age of 25. (The average undergraduate is 23 years old.)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/factbook/FactsFigures2018-2019.pdf|title=Facts & Figures 2018-2019|accessdate= 30 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Faculty and staff ===\nUAB has 21,245 employees, 11,810 in the university, including 2,543 faculty, and 9,435 in the UAB Health System.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/factbook/FactsFigures2018-2019.pdf|title=Facts & Figures 2018-2019|accessdate= 30 June 2019}}</ref>  91.3% of the faculty at UAB hold an academic or professional doctorate. Eight faculty members from UAB have been elected to the National [[Institute of Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iom.edu/Global/Directory.aspx?affiliationsearch=alabama&type={A75AB05B-9C36-4917-8FE3-ACA7E5CC580C} |title=Directory \u2013 Institute of Medicine |accessdate=November 7, 2011 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The student-faculty ratio at UAB is 18:1.\n\n=== Library ===\nUAB has eight library locations: Mervyn H. Sterne Library, Lister Hill Library of the Health Sciences, Lister Hill Library at University Hospital, Reynolds-Finley Historical Library, Alabama Museum of the Health Sciences, UAB Archives, UAB Digital Collections, and the 801 Building. \n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://library.uab.edu/locations|accessdate= 23 November 2019}}</ref>\nSterne Library holds 1.7 million print volumes while Lister Hill Library holds a little under 350,000.<ref name=\"fact-book\" />\n\n=== Rankings ===\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| ARWU_N = 67-94\n| ARWU_W = 201-300\n| THE_WSJ = 256\n| THES_W = 172\n| Forbes =  456\n| QS_W =\n| USNWR_NU = 166\n| USNWR_W = 175\n| Wamo_NU = 253\n}}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR graduate school rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR Grad School Rankings\">{{cite magazine|title=U.S. News Grad School Rankings: University of Alabama - Birmingham|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/university-of-alabama-at-birmingham-100663/overall-rankings|access-date=September 10, 2019|magazine=U.S. News & World Report}}</ref>\n|-\n| Education\n| 85\n|-\n| Engineering\n| 134\n|-\n| Medical: Primary Care\n| 35\n|-\n| Medical: Research\n| 30\n|-\n| Nursing: Doctorate\n| 16\n|-\n| Nursing: Master's\n| 18\n|}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR departmental rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR Grad School Rankings\"/>\n|-\n| Biological Sciences\n| 62\n|-\n| Chemistry\n| 122\n|-\n| Clinical Psychology\n| 74\n|-\n| Computer Science\n| 133\n|-\n| Health Care Management\n| 1\n|-\n| Mathematics\n| 127\n|-\n| Nursing: Anesthesia\n| 65\n|-\n| Occupational Therapy\n| 25\n|-\n| Physical Therapy\n| 20\n|-\n| Physician Assistant\n| 37\n|-\n| Physics\n| 124\n|-\n| Psychology\n| 98\n|-\n| Public Affairs\n| 68\n|-\n| Public Health\n| 19\n|-\n| Sociology\n| 96\n|-\n| Statistics\n| 89\n|}\nIn the 2020 ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' rankings, UAB was tied for the 166th best national university and was ranked the 79th best public university.<ref name=\"USNews\">{{cite web |title= University of Alabama-Birmingham |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/university-of-alabama-birmingham-1052/overall-rankings |work=U.S. News & World Report |access-date=September 10, 2019}}</ref> The UAB Master of Science in Health Administration program is the top ranked Health Care Management program in the U.S. News & World Report rankings and the only #1 program at UAB. Since 2015, the MSHA program has been the highest-ranking program at UAB.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/shp/news/home/programs/msha-program-number-one|title=UAB MSHA program new #1 in latest U.S. News & World Report rankings|accessdate= 11 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, UAB was named the Top Young University in the U.S. (50 years or younger) and among the top 10 globally in the Times Higher Education World University Rankings, which ranks effectiveness in areas such as teaching, research, citations, international outlooks and industry outcomes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/news/campus/item/9517-times-higher-education-ranks-uab-no-1-young-u-s-university-top-10-worldwide|title=Time Higher Education ranks UAB No. 1 young U.S. university, top 10 worldwide|author=Tyler Greer|accessdate= 29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Student life ==\nThere are over 150 student organizations on the UAB campus.\n\nThe UAB Model Arab League team is among the best government model teams in the nation with over five years of expansion and award-winning achievement including multiple \"outstanding delegation\" awards. The UAB Mock Trial team is consistently among the nation's best as a perennial Top 25 program. The program enjoyed its greatest success in 2006, when the team won the national title in the Silver Division defeating the defending national champions of [[Harvard University]].\n\n=== Recreation Center ===\n[[File:UAB REC CENTER.jpg|thumb|UAB Recreation Center]]\nOpened in 2005, the UAB Recreation Center serves the students, faculty, and alumni of UAB as well as the Birmingham community. The {{convert|150000|sqft|m2}} covers three floors: housing four basketball/volleyball courts, four racquetball courts (one of which can be converted to squash and four for wallyball), four aerobics studios, {{convert|18000|sqft|m2}} of weight and cardio-fitness areas, game room, KidsZone, aquatics center with both lap and leisure components, CenterCourt gym used for indoor soccer, floor hockey and badminton, juice bar, indoor track, and a [[climbing wall]]. The center includes free weights, court sports, swimming pools, group fitness classes, nutrition education, fitness areas, and a climbing wall.\n\n=== Greek life ===\nAbout six percent of undergraduate men and eight percent of undergraduate women are active in UAB's Greek system.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/university-of-alabama-birmingham-1052/student-life</ref> Twenty-two Greek Letter Organization (GLOs) are active on campus. Four governing bodies oversee the operations of university-sanctioned GLOs. These bodies act as umbrella organizations over the member GLOs. Among the differences between the governing bodies, the most important distinction are recruitment process and policies.\n\nThe Interfraternity Council (IFC) governs men's GLOs (also known as fraternities). Members are [[\u0391\u03a4\u03a9]], [[\u0394\u03a3\u03a6]], [[\u039b\u03a7\u0391]], [[\u03a4\u039a\u0395]], [[\u0398\u03a7]], [[\u03a6\u0393\u0394]] (FIJI), and [[\u03a0\u039a\u03a6]].\n\nThe Panhellenic Council (NPC) governs women's GLOs (also known as sororities). [[\u0391\u0393\u0394]] (colonized at UAB in 1978), [[\u0391\u039f\u03a0]] (1987), [[\u0391\u039e\u0394]] (1996), [[\u0394\u0393]] (1991), [[\u03a3\u039a]] (2015) and [[\u039a\u0394]] (2017).\n\nThe [[National Pan-Hellenic Council]] (NPHC) governs historically black GLOs. Member fraternities are [[\u0391\u03a6\u0391]] (\u0399\u039d chapter, founded at UAB in 1974), [[\u039a\u0391\u03a8]] (\u039a\u039a chapter, 1980), [[\u03a9\u03a8\u03a6]] (\u039a\u0394 chapter, 1972) and [[\u03a6\u0392\u03a3]] (HE chapter). Member sororities are [[\u0391\u039a\u0391]] (\u0399\u03a6 chapter, 1975), [[\u0394\u03a3\u0398]] (\u0399\u039b chapter, 1972), [[\u03a3\u0393\u03a1]] (\u039e\u039c chapter, 1996) and [[\u0396\u03a6\u0392]] (\u0393\u0398 chapter, 1977).\n\nThe Multicultural Greek Council (MGC) governs multicultural GLOs. Members include [[\u0394\u03a6\u03a9]], [[\u03a3\u03a3\u03a1]], [[\u0392\u03a7\u0398]], [[\u0394\u0395\u03a8]], and [[\u03a3\u039b\u0393]].\n\n=== Student media ===\nUAB Student Media is the home of the University of Alabama at Birmingham\u2019s student-run media outlets. They include ''Kaleidoscope'', an award-winning weekly newspaper; BlazeRadio, a 24-hour online radio station live on the TuneIn app; ''Aura Literary Arts Review'', a twice-yearly student magazine featuring fiction, creative non-fiction, art, photography, poetry and reviews; and UABTV, original, web-based video programming. UAB students operate all media. The articles, posts, newscasts and opinions are solely those of its student writers, producers, editors, deejays, etc. and do not reflect that of the university, its administrators or the Student Media advisors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uab.edu/studentmedia/|title=UAB Student Media |publisher=University of Alabama at Birmingham |access-date=November 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Intramurals ===\nThe school has an intramural program that runs year-round. Students and staff compete for league trophies in sports such as basketball, bowling, flag football, golf, soccer, softball, ultimate frisbee, and volleyball, or play in tournaments in billiards, racquetball, tennis, and other sports.\n\nOn August 29, 2018, UAB held a ribbon-cutting ceremony for an Intramural Complex, located at 1101 Fifth Ave. South, that is home for the university\u2019s intramural outdoor sports and club sports. The complex is a joint project between UAB Student Affairs and Campus Recreation through the UAB Facilities Division. Campus Recreation will oversee the fields, as well as program and schedule them. The space includes two full-size competition fields, two digital scoreboards, access to water and campus Wi-Fi, and a utility building that includes two all-gender restrooms, a storage space for sports equipment, and a utility room for lights and power\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/news/campus/item/9675-new-uab-intramural-sports-complex-set-to-open-aug-29|title=New UAB Intramural Sports Complex set to open Aug. 29|author=Shannon Thomason|accessdate= 29 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Health system ==\nThe '''UAB Health System''' (UABHS) is a partnership between UAB and the ''University of Alabama Health Services Foundation'' (UAHSF), a private not-for-profit medical practice made up of the faculty of the UAB School of Medicine. UABHS is governed by a board of directors which has representatives of UAHSF, the University of Alabama Board of Trustees, and UAB administrators. The UAB president is the ex officio chairperson of the UAB Health System. The CEO of the UABHS reports directly to the UAB Health System board and is appointed by the chairman of the board.\n\n[[UAB Hospital]] is the central institution of UABHS. It was formed as University Hospital in 1945 from the merger of Jefferson Hospital and Hillman Hospital, two private hospitals in the Southside of Birmingham acquired by the University of Alabama Board of Trustees. University Hospital was created to serve as the primary [[teaching hospital]] for the School of Medicine.\n\nThe other major institutions of UABHS include:\n* The [[Kirklin Clinic|Kirklin Clinic of UAB Hospital]], an outpatient clinic of UAB Hospital\n* Callahan Eye Foundation, founded independently as the Eye Foundation Hospital in 1963 and merged into UABHS in 1973,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://medicine.uab.edu/eyedoc/about/73714/|title=UAB \u2013 SOM \u2013 Dept of Ophthalmology \u2013 Home|author=Mellisa Eberle|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n* UAB Medicine Women and Infants Center\n* UAB Hospital-Highlands. Formerly [[HealthSouth]]'s flagship medical center in the [[Southside (Birmingham)|Southside]], UABHS acquired it in 2006. Highlands now serves as an acute care hospital. In 2011, Highlands was merged completely into UAB Hospital.\n* Spain Rehabilitation Center\n* UAB Medicine Health Centers, clinics operated and staffed by UABHS located throughout central Alabama\n* Viva Health, a [[health maintenance organization]] (HMO) which is a subsidiary of Triton Health Systems, a limited liability corporation based in Birmingham and owned by the UABHS\n\nIn addition UABHS manages, but does not operate, Medical West in [[Bessemer, Alabama|Bessemer]] and Baptist Health in [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]]. UABHS also has affiliations with the Birmingham VA Medical Center, [[Children's of Alabama|Children's Hospital of Alabama]], and [[Huntsville Hospital]] in [[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]].\n\n== Athletics ==\n{{Main|UAB Blazers}}\n[[File:UAB v Tulsa.jpg|thumb|left|UAB Blazers Men's Basketball vs. [[University of Tulsa|Tulsa]] at [[Bartow Arena]]]]\nUAB's athletic teams are known as the '''[[UAB Blazers|Blazers]]'''. The school athletic colors are forest green and old gold.<ref name=\"school-colors\">{{cite web |title=UAB Branding&nbsp;\u2013 Logos & Colors |url=http://www.uab.edu/brand/logos/official-colors |accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref>  The school is one of the 14 member institutions of [[Conference USA]] and participates in [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] of the [[NCAA]]. The men's basketball team, coached by [[Robert Ehsan]], plays in 8,508-seat [[Bartow Arena]].\n\nThe school started its intercollegiate athletic program in 1978.<ref name=\"fact-book\" /> The program was inaugurated with men's basketball by [[Gene Bartow]], who was [[John Wooden]]'s successor at [[UCLA]]. Bartow left UCLA after several exceptional seasons (52\u20139 over three seasons, including a berth in the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|Final Four]] in 1976) to head up the founding of the first UAB men's basketball team. He served as the school's first head basketball coach and [[athletic director]] for 18 years. Bartow led UAB to the [[National Invitation Tournament|NIT]] in the program's second year of existence, and followed that with seven straight [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Tournament]] appearances, including trips to the Sweet 16 in 1981 and the Elite Eight in 1982. Bartow retired from coaching in 1996 and, in 1997, UAB renamed its basketball venue from UAB Arena to Bartow Arena in his honor. In 30 years, UAB has made 13 NCAA appearances, three Sweet Sixteen appearances and an Elite Eight appearance, and has had 27 winning seasons, 19 of which were 20+ win seasons.\n\nIn addition to [[basketball]], UAB has programs in men's sports for [[baseball]], [[golf]], [[Association football|soccer]], and [[tennis]]. Women's sports programs include [[softball]], basketball, [[golf]], soccer, tennis, [[track and field]] (indoor and outdoor), [[Cross country running|cross country]], [[Shooting sports|rifle]] and [[volleyball]]. On November 11, 2010 UAB announced the addition of [[beach volleyball|sand volleyball]] and [[Ten-pin bowling|bowling]] beginning with the 2011\u20132012 academic year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uabsports.cstv.com/genrel/111110aaa.html|title=UAB To Add Women's Bowling, Women's Sand Volleyball \u2013 UAB Athletics Official Athletic Site|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nProfessional golfer [[Graeme McDowell]] (winner of the 2010 U.S. Open) played on the UAB golf team from 1998 to 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uab.edu/uabmagazine/2010/july/graememcdowell|title=UAB \u2013 Magazine \u2013 From Portrush to Pebble Beach|author=Grant Martin|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, the university announced that three sports were being eliminated at the end of the 2014\u20132015 academic year: [[American football|football]], [[bowling]] and [[Shooting sport|rifle]]. This was the result of an external review commissioned by the university that cited the rapidly changing landscape of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] and soaring operating costs.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gray|first1=Jeremy|title=It's official: UAB kills football program|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2014/12/uab_ends_football_program_rele.html|access-date=December 4, 2014|work=al.com|publisher=Alabama Media Group|date=December 2, 2014}}</ref> The football program became bowl-eligible for the first time in a decade following a win against [[Southern Miss]] two days before the announcement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Birdsong|first1=Nick|title=UAB football players in limbo, bowl outlook bleak|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2014/12/uab_football_players_in_limbo.html|access-date=December 4, 2014|work=al.com|publisher=Alabama Media Group|date=December 4, 2014}}</ref>\nOn June 1, 2015, Watts announced the reversal of the decision to end UAB football due to the large public opinion against the decision and the public fundraising of more than $27 million towards the program. The Blazers football program, rifle, and bowling programs were all reinstated with the former expected to resume play as early as 2016,.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2015/06/01/uab-blazers-football-program-reinstated|title=UAB Blazers Football Program Reinstated|website=SI.com |accessdate=June 1, 2015 |ref=uab20150601}}</ref> On June 4, 2015, Athletic Director Mark Ingram indicated that the 2017 season was a more reasonable timeline to field a football team for play.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/06/04/uab-ad-says-2017-a-more-ideal-target-for-football-revival/|title=UAB AD says 2017 a more ideal target for football revival|website=nbcsports.com |accessdate=June 6, 2015}}</ref> The football team resumed play for the 2017 NCAA Football season achieving an 8-5 record, the program's best since [[1993 UAB Blazers football team|1993]], and earning an invitation to the [[2017 Bahamas Bowl]], the team's first bowl game since 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fbschedules.com/ncaa-2017/team/uab|title=2017 UAB Football Schedule - FBSchedules.com|website=FBSchedules.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> Blazer Football had a historic season in 2018, earning the program\u2019s first Conference USA championship, first bowl win and best-ever record of 11-3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uabsports.com/news/2018/12/18/football-historic-night-sees-uab-defeat-niu-37-13-in-cheribundi-boca-raton-bowl.aspx|title=UAB \u2013 Historic Night Sees UAB Defeat NIU 37-13 in Cheribundi Boca Raton Bowl|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni and faculty ==\n{{Main|List of University of Alabama at Birmingham people}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.uabsports.com/ UAB Athletics website]\n\n{{University of Alabama at Birmingham}}\n{{Navboxes\n| titlestyle = {{CollegePrimaryStyle|UAB Blazers|color=white}}\n|list1 =\n{{University of Alabama System}}\n{{Conference USA navbox}}\n{{Colleges and universities in Alabama}}\n{{Southeastern Universities Research Association}}\n{{Birmingham Area Consortium for Higher Education}}\n{{Birmingham Landmarks}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alabama At Birmingham, University Of}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Alabama]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama at Birmingham| ]]\n[[Category:Urban 13 universities|Alabama at Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Schools of public health in the United States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Optometry schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:1969 establishments in Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|UAB|Universitat Aut\u00f2noma de Barcelona|Autonomous University of Barcelona|other uses}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name           = The University of Alabama at Birmingham\n|image          = University of Alabama at Birmingham seal.png\n|image_upright  = .7\n|established    = 1969\n|type           = [[Public university|Public]]\n|endowment      = $495.3 million <ref>{{cite web|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/uab-1052 |title=University of Alabama-Birmingham &#124; UAB &#124; Best College &#124; US News |publisher=Colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2016-03-25}}</ref>\n|president      = [[Ray L. Watts]]\n|provost        = Pam Benoit\n|city           = [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]]\n|state          = [[Alabama]]\n|country        = United States\n|students       = 21,923\n|undergrad      = 13,836\n|postgrad       = 8,087\n|faculty        = 2,605 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/facstaff/2018-UAB_workforce.pdf|title=UAB Work Force|accessdate=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n|coor           = {{coord|33.500000|-86.807500|type:city_region:US|display=inline}}\n|colors         = Green & White & Gold <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uab.edu/brand/home/standards/colors |title=UAB - Brand Toolkit - Colors |publisher=Uab.edu |accessdate=2016-03-25}}</ref><br />{{color box|#1E6B52}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n|nickname       = [[UAB Blazers|Blazers]]\n|mascot         = Blaze the [[Dragon]]\n|affiliations   = [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]], [[Great Cities' Universities]], [[University of Alabama System]]\n|sports         = 17 Intercollegiate Sports ([[NCAA]] [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] \u2013 [[Conference USA]])\n|website        = {{URL|www.uab.edu}}\n|logo           = UABirmingham logo.png\n|logo_upright   = 1.2\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Alabama at Birmingham''' ('''UAB''') is a [[Public university#United States|public]] [[List of research universities in the United States|research university]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama]]. Developed from an academic extension center established in 1936, the institution became a four-year campus in 1966 and a fully autonomous university in [[University of Alabama System|the University of Alabama System]] in 1969. \n\nUAB offers 140 programs of study in 12 academic divisions leading to [[bachelor's degree|bachelor's]], [[master's degree|master's]], [[doctorate|doctoral]], and [[professional degree|professional]] degrees in the [[social sciences|social]] and [[behavioral sciences]], the [[liberal arts]], [[business]], [[education]], [[engineering]], and health-related fields such as medicine, dentistry, optometry, nursing, and public health.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uasystem.edu//wp-content/uploads/2017/02/UAB-Financial-Report-Final.pdf|title=UAB 2016 Financial Report|work=University of Alabama at Birmingham|accessdate=23 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224131434/http://uasystem.edu//wp-content/uploads/2017/02/UAB-Financial-Report-Final.pdf|archive-date=2017-02-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the fall of 2018, 21,923 students from more than 110 countries were enrolled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/student-data/headcount-enrollment|title=UAB \u2013 Institutional Effectiveness and Analysis- Student Data Headcount Enrollment Report|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe UAB Health System, one of the largest [[academic medical center]]s in the United States, is affiliated with the university. [[UAB Hospital]] sponsors residency programs in medical specialties, including [[internal medicine]], neurology, physical medicine and rehabilitation, surgery, [[radiology]], and [[anesthesiology]]. UAB Hospital is the only [[Level I trauma center]] in Alabama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facs.org/trauma/verified.html|title=Trauma Centers|work=American College of Surgeons|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nUAB is the state's largest single employer, with more than 23,000 faculty and staff and over 53,000 jobs at the university and in the health system. An estimated 10 percent of the jobs in the [[Birmingham-Hoover Metropolitan Area]] and 1 in 31 jobs in the state of Alabama are directly or indirectly related to UAB. The university's overall annual economic impact was estimated to be $7.15 billion in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/impact/|title=UAB \u2013 How UAB powers Alabama's Economy - UAB Annual Impact on the Alabama Economy|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2017/10/uab_generates_715_billion_econ.html|title=UAB creates $7.15 billion in economic impact, study shows|author=Erin Edgemon|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{| style=\"float:right; margin:0.5em 0 0.5em 0.5em; width:20em; border:1px solid #a0a0a0; text-align:center; line-height:12px; font-size:x-small;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center; line-height:16px; font-size:small;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"color:white; background:#1E6B52;\"| Presidents of UAB\n|-\n| Dr. Joseph F. Volker\n| 1966\u20131976 (titled as VP for Birmingham Affairs, 1966-1969)<ref name=\"Chronology\"/>\n|-\n| Dr. S. Richardson Hill Jr.\n| 1977\u20131987\n|-\n| Dr. Charles A. McCallum\n| 1987\u20131993\n|-\n| Dr. J. Claude Bennett\n| 1993\u20131996\n|-\n| Mr. Paul Hardin\n| 1997 (Interim)\n|-\n| [[W. Ann Reynolds|Dr. W. Ann Reynolds]]\n| 1997\u20132002\n|-\n| [[Carol Garrison|Dr. Carol Z. Garrison]]\n| 2002\u20132012\n|-\n| [[Ray L. Watts|Dr. Ray L. Watts]]\n| 2013\u2013present\n|}\n\nIn 1936, in response to the rapid growth of the Birmingham metropolitan area and the need for the population to have access to a university education, the [[University of Alabama]] in [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]] established the '''Birmingham Extension Center'''.<ref name=\"Chronology\">{{cite web |title=UAB Chronology |url=http://library.uab.edu/locations/archives/uab-history |accessdate=May 29, 2011}}</ref>  The center operated in an old house in downtown Birmingham at 2131 6th Avenue North and enrolled 116 students. In 1945, UA's newly established four-year [[University of Alabama School of Medicine|School of Medicine]] moved from Tuscaloosa to Birmingham and took over management of Jefferson and Hillman hospitals. In 1957 enrollment at the extension center stood at 1,856. By 1959, research grants, training grants, and fellowships exceeded $1 million, and ground was broken for a new Children's Hospital.\n\nBy the 1960s, it grew apparent that the extension center was becoming a university in its own right. An engineering building was built close to the medical center in 1962, and in November 1966, the Extension Center and the School of Medicine were merged into the '''University of Alabama in Birmingham''', with Dr. Joseph Volker as \"Vice President for Birmingham Affairs\"\u2013reflecting that it was still treated as an offsite department of the main campus in Tuscaloosa. An Advisory Board for UAB was created in 1967. In 1969, the legislature created the [[University of Alabama System]]. UAB became one of three four-year institutions within the new system, which also included UA and the [[University of Alabama in Huntsville]] (UAH) in [[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]].  Volker became UAB's first president.<ref name=\"Chronology\"/>\n\nIn the 1970s, the university began a period of rapid growth. Enrollment at the beginning of the decade stood at 6,629, including 2,724 women. To accommodate the growing student population, UAB acquired land in the [[Southside (Birmingham)|Southside]]. UAB Mini Park (the predecessor to The UAB Green) was dedicated in 1977.\n\nThe university created an intercollegiate athletic program, joined the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] and began fielding teams beginning with golf in 1970 and men's basketball in 1978. The university's name was changed to the '''University of Alabama at Birmingham''' in 1984, simply exchanging the preposition \"In\" for \"at.\"\n\nBy 1990, UAB had awarded its 50,000th degree. In 1992, ''U.S. News and World Report'' named UAB as the #1 up-and-coming university in the United States. In 1993, UAB's economic impact on the Birmingham region was estimated at more than $1.5 billion per year (the figure would be $2 billion per year by 1998). In 1994, UAB became the first Alabama university to achieve \"Research University I\" status in the [[List of research universities in the United States|Carnegie Foundation classification]].\n\n== Campus ==\n[[File:University of Alabama at Birmingham Campus from Vulcan.jpg|thumb|upright=2.5|right|UAB campus and downtown Birmingham]]\nUAB is located in the [[Southside (Birmingham)|Southside]] neighborhood of downtown Birmingham. Occupying more than 100 city blocks<ref>{{cite web|url=https://alabamanewscenter.com/2018/06/06/uab-ranked-no-1-young-university-u-s/|title=UAB ranked No. 1 young university in the U.S.|author=Tyler Greer|accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref>, the roughly rectangular campus blends with the urban character of the Southside, stretching between 4th Ave S and 12th Ave S north to south and 8th St and 22nd St east to west. University Boulevard serves as the main axis of the rectangle and Campus Green sits approximately at the center.\n\nThe campus can be divided into three sections. The medical center occupies most of the campus east of Campus Green. The medical center is home to the health science schools and their teaching facilities, including the UAB Health System (UABHS). The medical center overlaps with the larger Birmingham Medical District where, in addition to UABHS, non-UAB affiliated hospitals such as the VA Medical Center Birmingham, Children's Hospital of Alabama and Cooper Green Mercy Hospital are located.\n\nThe academic heart of campus stretches from the Campus Green west and from University Boulevard south. Campus Green, developed between 2000 and 2007 as part of the move to convert the school from its previously commuter school feel into a more traditional residential campus, not only anchors the academic campus but serves as the centerpiece for the university as a whole. Most academics and arts buildings (excluding those associated with the medical center), residence halls, and student life facilities sit on or within two blocks of the Green.\n[[File:CAMPUS GREEN.jpg|thumb|Students relaxing on Campus Green]]\n\nAthletics facilities, including [[Bartow Arena]], are located on the far western side of campus.\n\nSince 1969, UAB has undergone extensive growth and construction projects are common across campus. Projects that are in planning, recently completed, or under construction include:<ref name=\"UAB President's Annual Report: 2019\">{{cite report |title=UAB Presdient's Annual Report New Kids on the Block|url=https://www.uab.edu/president/report|access-date=April 12, 2019}}</ref>\n* Collat School of Business and Bill L. Harbert Institute for Innovation and Entrepreneurship, ribbon cutting on August 28, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/erry-2018/08/e57ca0fc4d5292/tour-the-new-uab-collat-school.html|title=Tour the new UAB Collat School of Business opening today|author=Joe Songer|accessdate= 27 August 2018}}</ref>\n* Police and Public Safety Headquarters, ribbon cutting on August 9, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/news/campus/item/9664-new-uab-police-and-public-safety-headquarters-is-now-open|title=New UAB Police and Public Safety headquarters is now open|author=Tiffany Westry|accessdate= 9 August 2018}}</ref>\n* School of Nursing, ribbon cutting on September 6, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbrc.com/2018/09/06/uab-unveiling-new-state-of-the-art-building-school-nursing/|title=UAB unveiling new state-of-the-art building for School of Nursing|author=Shilo Groover|accessdate= 27 August 2018}}</ref>\n* College of Arts & Sciences University Hall - the first LEED-certified building on UAB campus - ribbon cutting on September, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.gmcnetwork.com/news/2019/09/uab-opens-its-first-leed-certified-building-on-campus/|title=UAB opens its first LEED-certified building on campus|author=GMC Network|accessdate= 4 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Organization and administration ==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:90%; line-height:1.4em; width:300px;\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''Academic Divisions of UAB'''\n|-\n| '''College/school''' || '''Year founded<ref name=\"fact-book\">{{cite report|url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/factbook/FactsFigures2016-2017.pdf|title=Facts & Figures 2016-2017|last=|first=|date=March 2017|publisher=University of Alabama at Birmingham|issue=|doi=|volume=|pmid=|accessdate=June 19, 2018}}</ref>'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |<hr />\n|-\n| College of Arts and Sciences || 2010\n|-\n| School of Business || 1971\n|-\n| School of Dentistry || 1945\n|-\n| School of Education || 1971\n|-\n| School of Engineering || 1971\n|-\n| School of Health Professions || 1969\n|-\n| School of Medicine || 1945\n|-\n| School of Nursing || 1967\n|-\n| School of Optometry || 1969\n|-\n| School of Public Health || 1981\n|-\n| Honors College || 2012\n|-\n| Graduate School || 1970\n|}\n\nUAB is an autonomous institution within the [[University of Alabama System]], which is governed by the Board of Trustees of the University of Alabama and headed by Chancellor of the University of Alabama. The board is self-nominating and composed of 15 elected members and two [[ex officio]] members. The makeup of the board is dictated by the [[Constitution of Alabama|Constitution of the State of Alabama]], and requires that the board be made up of three members from the [[congressional district]] that contains the Tuscaloosa campus, and two members from every other congressional district in Alabama. Board members are elected by the board and are confirmed by the [[Alabama Senate|Alabama State Senate]]. Board members may serve three consecutive six-year terms.<ref name=\"board\">{{cite web |title=The Board of Trustees of The University of Alabama, History and Purpose |url=http://www.uasystem.ua.edu/board/Board%20history.htm |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110515231429/http://www.uasystem.ua.edu/board/Board%20history.htm |archivedate=May 15, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe president of the University of Alabama at Birmingham is the principal executive officer of the university and is appointed by the chancellor with approval of the Board of Trustees. The president reports directly to the chancellor, and is responsible for the daily operations of the university. The president also acts as chairman of the board of the UAB Health System.<ref>{{cite web |title=UAB Medicine Leadership |url=http://www.uabmedicine.org/about-us/about-us-leadership |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref> Richard Marchase was named interim president on August 21, 2012, after the retirement of former president [[Carol Garrison]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Richard Marchase named interim president of UAB |url=http://www.uab.edu/news/latest/item/2671-dr-richard-marchase-named-interim-president-of-uab |date=August 21, 2012 |accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Richard Marchase, veteran administrator, named interim president of the University of Alabama at Birmingham |url=http://blog.al.com/spotnews/2012/08/richard_marchese_veteran_admin.html |date=August 21, 2012 |accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=UAB's Carol Garrison to step down after decade as president |url=http://www.uab.edu/news/latest/item/2658-uabs-carol-garrison-to-step-down-after-decade-as-president |date=August 16, 2012 |accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title =UAB President Carol Garrison stepping down after 10 years |url=http://blog.al.com/spotnews/2012/08/uab_president_carol_garrison_s_1.html |date=August 16, 2012 |accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref> In February 2013, Ray L. Watts became UAB's seventh president.<ref>{{cite web|title = Ray Watts name new president of UAB| url=https://www.bizjournals.com/birmingham/news/2013/02/08/ray-watts-named-new-president-of-uab.html|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Colleges ===\nUAB is composed of one college, nine schools and the Graduate School. Together, these divisions offer 56 bachelor's degree programs, 59 master's degree programs, and 40 doctoral programs. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/factbook/sections/52-54_FactsFigures2018_DegreesOfferedAtUAB.pdf|title=Degrees Offered at UAB, Student Information|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\nBefore 2010, the schools of Arts and Humanities, Social and Behavioral Sciences, Natural Science and Mathematics, and Education were separate, degree-granting units within the university. The schools were merged into a single college (the first at UAB): the College of Arts and Sciences, with Education retaining its identity as a distinct unit within the new college. University leaders cited efficiency, curricula, and more opportunity for interdisciplinary research and cooperation for the restructuring.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://main.uab.edu/Sites/MediaRelations/articles/70134/ |title=UAB Announces Realignment; Forming a College of Arts & Sciences |access-date=2011-05-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925151320/http://main.uab.edu/Sites/MediaRelations/articles/70134/ |archive-date=2011-09-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Endowment ===\nUAB's endowment stood at $495.3 million in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/uab-1052 |title=University of Alabama-Birmingham &#124; UAB &#124; Best College &#124; US News |publisher=Colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2019-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, the university launched a capital campaign with a goal of $250 million. When it ended in 2003, the UAB Capital Campaign had raised over $388.7 million.\n\nThe Campaign for UAB launched publicly in October 2013 with a goal of raising $1 billion. Prior to the public launch of the campaign, UAB had already received over $420 million in donations. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uab.edu/give/campaign/foruab|title=UAB \u2013 The Campaign for UAB \u2013 The Campaign for UAB|author=Linda Gunter|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref> In 2018, UAB exceeded the $1 billion goal of The Campaign for UAB, the most ambitious fundraising effort in the university\u2019s history. Putting the Campaign over its goal was the largest single gift ever made to UAB:  $30 million from O\u2019Neal Industries and its shareholders to name the O\u2019Neal Comprehensive Cancer Center at UAB.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/news/campus/item/9987-thanks-a-billion-the-campaign-for-uab-surpasses-1-billion|title=UAB \u2013 UAB News \u2013 Thanks a billion: The Campaign for UAB surpasses $1 billion|author=Tyler Greer|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/news/health/item/10005-o-neal-industries-gift-will-leverage-advances-in-cancer-research-patient-care-and-biotechnology-growth  |title=UAB \u2013 UAB News\u2013 O'Neal Industries gift will leverage advances in cancer research, patient care and biotechnology growth|author=Jeff Hansen|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>  \n\n== Academics ==\n{| style=\"text-align:center; float:right;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Average tuition for full-time students (AY 2013\u20132014)<ref name=\"tuition\">{{cite web |title=2013-2014: Tuition Summary, University of Alabama at Birmingham| url=https://www.uab.edu/students/current/paying-for-college/detailed-tuition-and-fees |accessdate= March 5, 2014}}</ref>\n! - !! Alabama resident !! Non-resident\n|-\n| Undergraduate (2 x 15cr) || $8,904|| $20,394\n|-\n| Graduate (2 x 12cr)|| $8,934 || $20,454\n|-\n| Optometry (yr)|| $8,045 || $17,140\n|-\n| Dentistry (yr)|| $11,861 || $27,380\n|-\n| Medicine (yr)|| $24,510 || $58,590\n|}\n\nUAB is a large, four-year primarily non-residential research university.<ref name=\"Carnegie1\">{{cite web |title=Carnegie Classifications \u2013 University of Alabama at Birmingham |url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=100663 |publisher=Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching |accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref> UAB has been accredited by the [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]] since 1970, according to the [[United States Department of Education|U.S. Department of Education]].<ref name=\"USDOE\">{{cite web |title=College Navigator \u2013 University of Alabama at Birmingham |url=http://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?q=University+of+Alabama+at+Birmingham&s=all&id=100663 |publisher=National Center for Education Statistics, United States Department of Education Institute for Education Sciences |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>  Undergraduates comprise a majority of the total university enrollment. Part-time and transfer student comprise a sizable portion of the undergraduate student body. The undergraduate instructional program provides a balance between professional programs of study and the liberal arts (meaning the number of degrees awarded in the two areas is similar), and there is a high level of co-existence between the graduate and undergraduate programs (meaning that the majority of undergraduate program have graduate degree program counterparts). The university has a high level of research activity and has a graduate instructional program emphasizing doctorates in [[STEM fields]] as well as  professional programs in the health and veterinary sciences. UAB is one of only 108 universities in the country (and one of only two in Alabama) with the \"very high level\" research rating.<ref name=\"carnegie2\">{{cite web |title= Carnegie Classifications \u2013 Standard Listings |url=http://classifications.carnegiefoundation.org/lookup_listings/srp.php?clq={%22basic2005_ids%22%3A%2215%22}|accessdate=June 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe academic calendar is based on the [[semester#United States|semester system]], which divides the [[academic year#Academic year|academic year]], lasting from mid-August to early May, into two 15-week semesters (fall and spring) and the summer. The fall semester ends in early December and the spring term begins in early January. The summer, which lasts from mid-May to August, is divided into a number of sessions: a 12-week session, a 3-week \"mini-semester\" in May, a nine-week session in June and July, and two four-week sessions in June and July, respectively.<ref name=\"academic-calender\">{{cite web |title=Academic Calendar |url=http://main.uab.edu/Sites/students/services/registration/48843/ |accessdate=May 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713115606/http://main.uab.edu/Sites/students/services/registration/48843/ |archive-date=July 13, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The schools of medicine and dentistry follow an academic calendar beginning in July and ending in late May/early June.<ref name=\"medschool-calendar\">{{cite web |title=Academic Year Term Dates, UAB School of Medicine |url=http://medicine.uab.edu/education/62006/ |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"dentalschool-calender\">{{cite web |title=Academic Calendar, School of Dentistry |url=http://www.dental.uab.edu/students/current-students/academic-calendar1.html |accessdate=May 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn academic year 2016\u20132017, UAB awarded a total 2,384 bachelor's degrees; 1,795 master's degrees, 33 educational specialist degrees; 125 research doctorates; and 391 professional doctorates.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/factbook/FactsFigures2017-2018.pdf/|title=UAB \u20132017-2018 Facts & Figures|accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Student profile ===\nIn fall semester 2018, the UAB student body consisted of 13,836 undergraduates, 6,933 graduate students and 1,154 professional doctoral students from all 67 Alabama counties, all 50 states and more than 110 foreign countries. In fall semester 2018, 5,737 students were enrolled in the College of Arts and Sciences, 1,775 in Education, 3,432 in Business, 271 in Dentistry, 1,486 in Engineering, 2,431 in Health Professions, 324 in Joint Health Sciences, 694 in Medicine, 2,736 in Nursing, 217 in Optometry, 752 in Public Health, while 1,902 were undecided.\n\nOf the undergraduate student body, 33.2% are from [[Jefferson County, Alabama|Jefferson County]], 14.4% are from other counties in the [[Birmingham\u2013Hoover Metropolitan Area|Birmingham metropolitan area]], specifically [[Blount County, Alabama|Blount]], [[Shelby County, Alabama|Shelby]], [[St. Clair County, Alabama|St. Clair]] and [[Walker County, Alabama|Walker]] counties. 29.4% come from the rest of Alabama, 18.2% from the rest of the United States, while international students comprise 4.8%. The male-to-female ratio among undergraduates is 2:3. Reflecting one of the core reasons for UAB's founding, a large percentage of undergraduates are from non-traditional demographics. 27.4% of undergraduates are part-time students, and 18.7% are above the age of 25. (The average undergraduate is 23 years old.)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/factbook/FactsFigures2018-2019.pdf|title=Facts & Figures 2018-2019|accessdate= 30 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Faculty and staff ===\nUAB has 21,245 employees, 11,810 in the university, including 2,543 faculty, and 9,435 in the UAB Health System.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/institutionaleffectiveness/images/factbook/FactsFigures2018-2019.pdf|title=Facts & Figures 2018-2019|accessdate= 30 June 2019}}</ref>  91.3% of the faculty at UAB hold an academic or professional doctorate. Eight faculty members from UAB have been elected to the National [[Institute of Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iom.edu/Global/Directory.aspx?affiliationsearch=alabama&type={A75AB05B-9C36-4917-8FE3-ACA7E5CC580C} |title=Directory \u2013 Institute of Medicine |accessdate=November 7, 2011 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The student-faculty ratio at UAB is 18:1.\n\n=== Library ===\nUAB has eight library locations: Mervyn H. Sterne Library, Lister Hill Library of the Health Sciences, Lister Hill Library at University Hospital, Reynolds-Finley Historical Library, Alabama Museum of the Health Sciences, UAB Archives, UAB Digital Collections, and the 801 Building. \n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://library.uab.edu/locations|accessdate= 23 November 2019}}</ref>\nSterne Library holds 1.7 million print volumes while Lister Hill Library holds a little under 350,000.<ref name=\"fact-book\" />\n\n=== Rankings ===\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| ARWU_N = 67-94\n| ARWU_W = 201-300\n| THE_WSJ = 256\n| THES_W = 172\n| Forbes =  456\n| QS_W =\n| USNWR_NU = 166\n| USNWR_W = 175\n| Wamo_NU = 253\n}}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR graduate school rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR Grad School Rankings\">{{cite magazine|title=U.S. News Grad School Rankings: University of Alabama - Birmingham|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/university-of-alabama-at-birmingham-100663/overall-rankings|access-date=September 10, 2019|magazine=U.S. News & World Report}}</ref>\n|-\n| Education\n| 85\n|-\n| Engineering\n| 134\n|-\n| Medical: Primary Care\n| 35\n|-\n| Medical: Research\n| 30\n|-\n| Nursing: Doctorate\n| 16\n|-\n| Nursing: Master's\n| 18\n|}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR departmental rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR Grad School Rankings\"/>\n|-\n| Biological Sciences\n| 62\n|-\n| Chemistry\n| 122\n|-\n| Clinical Psychology\n| 74\n|-\n| Computer Science\n| 133\n|-\n| Health Care Management\n| 1\n|-\n| Mathematics\n| 127\n|-\n| Nursing: Anesthesia\n| 65\n|-\n| Occupational Therapy\n| 25\n|-\n| Physical Therapy\n| 20\n|-\n| Physician Assistant\n| 37\n|-\n| Physics\n| 124\n|-\n| Psychology\n| 98\n|-\n| Public Affairs\n| 68\n|-\n| Public Health\n| 19\n|-\n| Sociology\n| 96\n|-\n| Statistics\n| 89\n|}\nIn the 2020 ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' rankings, UAB was tied for the 166th best national university and was ranked the 79th best public university.<ref name=\"USNews\">{{cite web |title= University of Alabama-Birmingham |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/university-of-alabama-birmingham-1052/overall-rankings |work=U.S. News & World Report |access-date=September 10, 2019}}</ref> The UAB Master of Science in Health Administration program is the top ranked Health Care Management program in the U.S. News & World Report rankings and the only #1 program at UAB. Since 2015, the MSHA program has been the highest-ranking program at UAB. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/shp/news/home/programs/msha-program-number-one|title=UAB MSHA program new #1 in latest U.S. News & World Report rankings|accessdate= 11 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, UAB was named the Top Young University in the U.S. (50 years or younger) and among the top 10 globally in the Times Higher Education World University Rankings, which ranks effectiveness in areas such as teaching, research, citations, international outlooks and industry outcomes. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/news/campus/item/9517-times-higher-education-ranks-uab-no-1-young-u-s-university-top-10-worldwide|title=Time Higher Education ranks UAB No. 1 young U.S. university, top 10 worldwide|author=Tyler Greer|accessdate= 29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Student life ==\nThere are over 150 student organizations on the UAB campus.\n\nThe UAB Model Arab League team is among the best government model teams in the nation with over five years of expansion and award-winning achievement including multiple \"outstanding delegation\" awards. The UAB Mock Trial team is consistently among the nation's best as a perennial Top 25 program. The program enjoyed its greatest success in 2006, when the team won the national title in the Silver Division defeating the defending national champions of [[Harvard University]].\n\n=== Recreation Center ===\n[[File:UAB REC CENTER.jpg|thumb|UAB Recreation Center]]\nOpened in 2005, the UAB Recreation Center serves the students, faculty, and alumni of UAB as well as the Birmingham community. The {{convert|150000|sqft|m2}} covers three floors: housing four basketball/volleyball courts, four racquetball courts (one of which can be converted to squash and four for wallyball), four aerobics studios, {{convert|18000|sqft|m2}} of weight and cardio-fitness areas, game room, KidsZone, aquatics center with both lap and leisure components, CenterCourt gym used for indoor soccer, floor hockey and badminton, juice bar, indoor track, and a [[climbing wall]]. The center includes free weights, court sports, swimming pools, group fitness classes, nutrition education, fitness areas, and a climbing wall.\n\n=== Greek life ===\nAbout six percent of undergraduate men and eight percent of undergraduate women are active in UAB's Greek system.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/university-of-alabama-birmingham-1052/student-life</ref> Twenty-two Greek Letter Organization (GLOs) are active on campus. Four governing bodies oversee the operations of university-sanctioned GLOs. These bodies act as umbrella organizations over the member GLOs. Among the differences between the governing bodies, the most important distinction are recruitment process and policies.\n\nThe Interfraternity Council (IFC) governs men's GLOs (also known as fraternities). Members are [[\u0391\u03a4\u03a9]], [[\u0394\u03a3\u03a6]], [[\u039b\u03a7\u0391]], [[\u03a4\u039a\u0395]], [[\u0398\u03a7]], [[\u03a6\u0393\u0394]] (FIJI), and [[\u03a0\u039a\u03a6]].\n\nThe Panhellenic Council (NPC) governs women's GLOs (also known as sororities). [[\u0391\u0393\u0394]] (colonized at UAB in 1978), [[\u0391\u039f\u03a0]] (1987), [[\u0391\u039e\u0394]] (1996), [[\u0394\u0393]] (1991), [[\u03a3\u039a]] (2015) and [[\u039a\u0394]] (2017).\n\nThe [[National Pan-Hellenic Council]] (NPHC) governs historically black GLOs. Member fraternities are [[\u0391\u03a6\u0391]] (\u0399\u039d chapter, founded at UAB in 1974), [[\u039a\u0391\u03a8]] (\u039a\u039a chapter, 1980), [[\u03a9\u03a8\u03a6]] (\u039a\u0394 chapter, 1972) and [[\u03a6\u0392\u03a3]] (HE chapter). Member sororities are [[\u0391\u039a\u0391]] (\u0399\u03a6 chapter, 1975), [[\u0394\u03a3\u0398]] (\u0399\u039b chapter, 1972), [[\u03a3\u0393\u03a1]] (\u039e\u039c chapter, 1996) and [[\u0396\u03a6\u0392]] (\u0393\u0398 chapter, 1977).\n\nThe Multicultural Greek Council (MGC) governs multicultural GLOs. Members include [[\u0394\u03a6\u03a9]], [[\u03a3\u03a3\u03a1]], [[\u0392\u03a7\u0398]], [[\u0394\u0395\u03a8]], and [[\u03a3\u039b\u0393]].\n\n=== Student media ===\nUAB Student Media is the home of the University of Alabama at Birmingham\u2019s student-run media outlets. They include ''Kaleidoscope'', an award-winning weekly newspaper; BlazeRadio, a 24-hour online radio station live on the TuneIn app; ''Aura Literary Arts Review'', a twice-yearly student magazine featuring fiction, creative non-fiction, art, photography, poetry and reviews; and UABTV, original, web-based video programming. UAB students operate all media. The articles, posts, newscasts and opinions are solely those of its student writers, producers, editors, deejays, etc. and do not reflect that of the university, its administrators or the Student Media advisors. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uab.edu/studentmedia/|title=UAB Student Media |publisher=University of Alabama at Birmingham |access-date=November 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Intramurals ===\nThe school has an intramural program that runs year-round. Students and staff compete for league trophies in sports such as basketball, bowling, flag football, golf, soccer, softball, ultimate frisbee, and volleyball, or play in tournaments in billiards, racquetball, tennis, and other sports.<br><br>\nOn August 29, 2018, UAB held a ribbon-cutting ceremony for an Intramural Complex, located at 1101 Fifth Ave. South, that is home for the university\u2019s intramural outdoor sports and club sports. The complex is a joint project between UAB Student Affairs and Campus Recreation through the UAB Facilities Division. Campus Recreation will oversee the fields, as well as program and schedule them. The space includes two full-size competition fields, two digital scoreboards, access to water and campus Wi-Fi, and a utility building that includes two all-gender restrooms, a storage space for sports equipment, and a utility room for lights and power\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uab.edu/news/campus/item/9675-new-uab-intramural-sports-complex-set-to-open-aug-29|title=New UAB Intramural Sports Complex set to open Aug. 29|author=Shannon Thomason|accessdate= 29 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Health system ==\nThe '''UAB Health System''' (UABHS) is a partnership between UAB and the ''University of Alabama Health Services Foundation'' (UAHSF), a private not-for-profit medical practice made up of the faculty of the UAB School of Medicine. UABHS is governed by a board of directors which has representatives of UAHSF, the University of Alabama Board of Trustees, and UAB administrators. The UAB president is the ex officio chairperson of the UAB Health System. The CEO of the UABHS reports directly to the UAB Health System board and is appointed by the chairman of the board.\n\n[[UAB Hospital]] is the central institution of UABHS. It was formed as University Hospital in 1945 from the merger of Jefferson Hospital and Hillman Hospital, two private hospitals in the Southside of Birmingham acquired by the University of Alabama Board of Trustees. University Hospital was created to serve as the primary [[teaching hospital]] for the School of Medicine.\n\nThe other major institutions of UABHS include:\n* The [[Kirklin Clinic|Kirklin Clinic of UAB Hospital]], an outpatient clinic of UAB Hospital\n* Callahan Eye Foundation, founded independently as the Eye Foundation Hospital in 1963 and merged into UABHS in 1973,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://medicine.uab.edu/eyedoc/about/73714/|title=UAB \u2013 SOM \u2013 Dept of Ophthalmology \u2013 Home|author=Mellisa Eberle|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n* UAB Medicine Women and Infants Center\n* UAB Hospital-Highlands. Formerly [[HealthSouth]]'s flagship medical center in the [[Southside (Birmingham)|Southside]], UABHS acquired it in 2006. Highlands now serves as an acute care hospital. In 2011, Highlands was merged completely into UAB Hospital.\n* Spain Rehabilitation Center\n* UAB Medicine Health Centers, clinics operated and staffed by UABHS located throughout central Alabama\n* Viva Health, a [[health maintenance organization]] (HMO) which is a subsidiary of Triton Health Systems, a limited liability corporation based in Birmingham and owned by the UABHS\n\nIn addition UABHS manages, but does not operate, Medical West in [[Bessemer, Alabama|Bessemer]] and Baptist Health in [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]]. UABHS also has affiliations with the Birmingham VA Medical Center, [[Children's of Alabama|Children's Hospital of Alabama]], and [[Huntsville Hospital]] in [[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville]].\n\n== Athletics ==\n{{Main|UAB Blazers}}\n[[File:UAB v Tulsa.jpg|thumb|left|UAB Blazers Men's Basketball vs. [[University of Tulsa|Tulsa]] at [[Bartow Arena]]]]\nUAB's athletic teams are known as the '''[[UAB Blazers|Blazers]]'''. The school athletic colors are forest green and old gold.<ref name=\"school-colors\">{{cite web |title=UAB Branding&nbsp;\u2013 Logos & Colors |url=http://www.uab.edu/brand/logos/official-colors |accessdate=December 15, 2010}}</ref>  The school is one of the 14 member institutions of [[Conference USA]] and participates in [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] of the [[NCAA]]. The men's basketball team, coached by [[Robert Ehsan]], plays in 8,508-seat [[Bartow Arena]].\n\nThe school started its intercollegiate athletic program in 1978.<ref name=\"fact-book\" /> The program was inaugurated with men's basketball by [[Gene Bartow]], who was [[John Wooden]]'s successor at [[UCLA]]. Bartow left UCLA after several exceptional seasons (52\u20139 over three seasons, including a berth in the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|Final Four]] in 1976) to head up the founding of the first UAB men's basketball team. He served as the school's first head basketball coach and [[athletic director]] for 18 years. Bartow led UAB to the [[National Invitation Tournament|NIT]] in the program's second year of existence, and followed that with seven straight [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Tournament]] appearances, including trips to the Sweet 16 in 1981 and the Elite Eight in 1982. Bartow retired from coaching in 1996 and, in 1997, UAB renamed its basketball venue from UAB Arena to Bartow Arena in his honor. In 30 years, UAB has made 13 NCAA appearances, three Sweet Sixteen appearances and an Elite Eight appearance, and has had 27 winning seasons, 19 of which were 20+ win seasons.\n\nIn addition to [[basketball]], UAB has programs in men's sports for [[baseball]], [[golf]], [[Association football|soccer]], and [[tennis]]. Women's sports programs include [[softball]], basketball, [[golf]], soccer, tennis, [[track and field]] (indoor and outdoor), [[Cross country running|cross country]], [[Shooting sports|rifle]] and [[volleyball]]. On November 11, 2010 UAB announced the addition of [[beach volleyball|sand volleyball]] and [[Ten-pin bowling|bowling]] beginning with the 2011\u20132012 academic year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uabsports.cstv.com/genrel/111110aaa.html|title=UAB To Add Women's Bowling, Women's Sand Volleyball \u2013 UAB Athletics Official Athletic Site|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nProfessional golfer [[Graeme McDowell]] (winner of the 2010 U.S. Open) played on the UAB golf team from 1998 to 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uab.edu/uabmagazine/2010/july/graememcdowell|title=UAB \u2013 Magazine \u2013 From Portrush to Pebble Beach|author=Grant Martin|accessdate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, the university announced that three sports were being eliminated at the end of the 2014\u20132015 academic year: [[American football|football]], [[bowling]] and [[Shooting sport|rifle]]. This was the result of an external review commissioned by the university that cited the rapidly changing landscape of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] and soaring operating costs.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gray|first1=Jeremy|title=It's official: UAB kills football program|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2014/12/uab_ends_football_program_rele.html|access-date=December 4, 2014|work=al.com|publisher=Alabama Media Group|date=December 2, 2014}}</ref> The football program became bowl-eligible for the first time in a decade following a win against [[Southern Miss]] two days before the announcement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Birdsong|first1=Nick|title=UAB football players in limbo, bowl outlook bleak|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2014/12/uab_football_players_in_limbo.html|access-date=December 4, 2014|work=al.com|publisher=Alabama Media Group|date=December 4, 2014}}</ref>\nOn June 1, 2015, Watts announced the reversal of the decision to end UAB football due to the large public opinion against the decision and the public fundraising of more than $27 million towards the program. The Blazers football program, rifle, and bowling programs were all reinstated with the former expected to resume play as early as 2016,.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2015/06/01/uab-blazers-football-program-reinstated|title=UAB Blazers Football Program Reinstated|website=SI.com |accessdate=June 1, 2015 |ref=uab20150601}}</ref> On June 4, 2015, Athletic Director Mark Ingram indicated that the 2017 season was a more reasonable timeline to field a football team for play.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/06/04/uab-ad-says-2017-a-more-ideal-target-for-football-revival/|title=UAB AD says 2017 a more ideal target for football revival|website=nbcsports.com |accessdate=June 6, 2015}}</ref> The football team resumed play for the 2017 NCAA Football season achieving an 8-5 record, the program's best since [[1993 UAB Blazers football team|1993]], and earning an invitation to the [[2017 Bahamas Bowl]], the team's first bowl game since 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fbschedules.com/ncaa-2017/team/uab|title=2017 UAB Football Schedule - FBSchedules.com|website=FBSchedules.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> Blazer Football had a historic season in 2018, earning the program\u2019s first Conference USA championship, first bowl win and best-ever record of 11-3. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://uabsports.com/news/2018/12/18/football-historic-night-sees-uab-defeat-niu-37-13-in-cheribundi-boca-raton-bowl.aspx|title=UAB \u2013 Historic Night Sees UAB Defeat NIU 37-13 in Cheribundi Boca Raton Bowl|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni and faculty ==\n{{Main|List of University of Alabama at Birmingham people}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.uabsports.com/ UAB Athletics website]\n\n{{University of Alabama at Birmingham}}\n{{Navboxes\n| titlestyle = {{CollegePrimaryStyle|UAB Blazers|color=white}}\n|list1 =\n{{University of Alabama System}}\n{{Conference USA navbox}}\n{{Colleges and universities in Alabama}}\n{{Southeastern Universities Research Association}}\n{{Birmingham Area Consortium for Higher Education}}\n{{Birmingham Landmarks}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alabama At Birmingham, University Of}}\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Alabama]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama at Birmingham| ]]\n[[Category:Urban 13 universities|Alabama at Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Schools of public health in the United States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Optometry schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:1969 establishments in Alabama]]\n", "name_user": "Naraht", "label": "safe", "comment": "cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Alabama_at_Birmingham"}
